Republican strategy to resist Obama&#39;s re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that election fraud in the United States is more rare than deaths from lightning.
In addition, Republican lawyers have counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
This is why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that make it difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon took off after the November 2010 elections, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed restricting voting rights in 41 states.
New electoral laws require voters to present photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of expression of will and take away the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no US state required voters to show photo ID.
Indiana became the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The US Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to show photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identification as a health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people who have reached the legal age to vote, do not have a photo ID issued by their state government.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
That being said, the cost of obtaining the required ID often exceeds $ 100.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $ 35,000, 18% of citizens over 65, and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years old do not have the required photo ID.
But that&#39;s not all.
Student voters believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use a photo ID issued by their school.
But the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use the certificates issued by these clubs to vote.
Until 2004, no state required proof of US citizenship to vote.
The first time such a requirement was introduced was in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are US citizens.
These measures are apparently aimed at restricting the voting of Hispanics.
It is believed that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 abolishing voting day voter registration in eight states.
They also limited the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those who wish to register.
This limitation did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped enroll about 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have resulted in a 17% drop in the registration rate of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the early voting period.
For example, during the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of early voters were African American, although the latter made up only 13% of the state&#39;s total voters.
The same thing happened with the Hispanics.
Representing only 11% of voters, they constituted 24% of citizens who voted early.
In contrast to whites, who, forming 76% of voters, among those who voted early were only 46%.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters actively oppose laws restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended with the intervention of the Attorney General of the United States.
This made it possible to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring photo identification.
However, the new rules that have come into force will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the electoral right in the 2012 elections.
Democratic critics denounce the biased laws that were passed, seeing them as clearly intended to influence the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral votes required to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Prostate Cancer Screening: To Get The Test Or Not?
In fact, the PSA test produces sometimes erroneous results, false negative and sometimes false positive, which lead to useless medical intervention.
Men who are already reluctant to undergo medical examination have something to doubt even more.
Pass the test or not?
We asked the opinion of two experts.
In studies conducted in the United States, there were numerous cases of infection among the study groups, so the findings are difficult to interpret and difficult to make any clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, found different mortality rates in those who were screened and those who did not.
This study also showed, after 12 years of follow-up, that those who did not get screened were 30-40% more likely to develop metastases.
Therefore, I would recommend taking the test from the age of 50, or from 40 if one of the direct relatives has had prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent are also at increased risk.
Making the right decision as soon as cancer is found is key.
Cancer can be aggressive or slow-moving.
The patient needs to be educated about the risk of his cancer, offering him possible options, without compulsory treatment for prostate cancer, which does not pose a threat to life in the long term, but making a choice, in these cases, in favor of active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men diagnosed with cancer will not receive treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to life.
We will offer them active monitoring, and if the disease progresses, we will begin treatment.
Increasingly, we are defining precisely the criteria for deciding who should or should not receive treatment.
Thus, I would recommend taking the test anyway.
But it is also important to consult with your doctor to determine whether or not you need to take this test.
In collaboration with the International Association of Urology, Movember has created a tool to assess the pros and cons of taking a PSA test.
