The Higgs Boson in Detail
Last summer, the message that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused quite a stir - and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the Universe, neither more nor less.
It is also the last particle predicted by the Standard Model — our best, or at least the “least imperfect” description of the nature and behavior of matter — but which has never been empirically detected before.
But physicists are not yet completely sure that we are talking about the Higgs boson.
We know, beyond a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a truly new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data presented this week at a major physics convention in Kyoto seem to support this, although some data are still lacking to be sure.
Imagine, however, that we are talking about the Higgs boson, since the chances of error seem minimal, and let&#39;s see what this means.
There is, in this world, one absolutely inevitable law, which says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to get around this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise you will harm yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of a similar nature: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they stay in the same &quot;quantum state&quot; - this &quot;state&quot; is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens, called fermions, who prudently obey the Pauli principle.
In the other, the bosons, a vile gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least for this principle, which means that they can safely end up in the same place at the same time - are scurrying about.
According to the website (by the way, completely unusual) Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratory, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and &quot;force particles&quot; through which the main forces of nature propagate and to to which the Higgs boson belongs in some way.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly commonplace boson: the photon, or &quot;particle of light&quot;, which is the &quot;courier&quot; of electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when one particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it &quot;disturbs&quot; the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this &quot;disturbance&quot; an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and, therefore, one of the bosons of &quot;force carriers&quot;.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be &quot;violated&quot;.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you need to reach very, very high energies, as if we were talking about a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large stone.
This is why a huge particle accelerator is needed, like the one operated at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring 27 km in diameter! - to achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with an electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never stick to the refrigerator itself.
Likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like a photon, by the way) do not.
So what does all this research &quot;can bring&quot;, Ms Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to validate the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to grope for discrepancies between observations and forecasts of the SM.
In addition, some of them are eager for such a discrepancy to be revealed, since the slightest discrepancy can open the door for &quot;new physics&quot; and plug some holes in the Model.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) Or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh-oh!).
But so far no such discrepancies have been found at CERN.
Effects
The benefits of these studies to the everyday life of the average person are harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that they are not.
Look: at the very beginning of the 60s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell&#39;s laboratories could not even imagine what kind of revolution their work would cause.
They foresaw their applications in science, but nothing more.
Indeed, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first cw laser (the previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that initially the laser was viewed more as &quot; laboratory gadget &quot;.
Imagine ...
And in addition, an appendix can be found for the toolkit accompanying the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original purpose, now serves as the &quot;eye&quot; for all digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die ... | &quot;Debt&quot;
The Commission for a Dignified Death in Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this critical area.
Debt tried to get a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Monterege.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him from the inside gave him a two-year reprieve.
“I was given five years, I lived for seven,” he says, between life and death, lying in bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care shelter in Beleu, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, it’s impossible to prepare for it,” he says.
The disease is doing its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet on your own and even eating on your own.
Sitting at a table with a delicious lunch, he gives up and agrees to be helped to eat.
He invigorates, even manages to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, take him to the bath.
Courage in the face of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to have my diarrhea cured, it&#39;s humiliating,” he admits.
Several hours later, staff found a cure for the ailment.
&quot;Throughout our lives, we are taught that men should urinate while standing,&quot; says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois shelter.
To regress to the state of a child is an unbearable humiliation for some.
&quot;It all depends on the person&#39;s ability to&quot; come to terms with decline, &quot;he says.
Because, according to many palliative care people, important events happen in the midst of this decline.
Patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care facility are all cancer patients.
Forecasts give them a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses no longer provides what is called &quot;curative&quot; help.
Ms. A., 89 years old, is most afraid of dying &quot;conscious from suffocation.&quot;
But the disease allowed me to recognize my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I don’t want anything else in life,” she says, before allowing her to put on a mask to ease breathing.
She is still waiting in the coming days for the last visit of her son, who came from Italy.
At Victor-Gadbois Shelter, with the help of a group of volunteers, body care and nutrition are provided.
This is palliative care that remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care place for every 11,700 inhabitants.
This is very little, considering that sooner or later we will all die.
Here life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the doctors at the orphanage.
Whether it&#39;s physical, emotional or mental comfort.
For the dying person, we will agree to provide mouthwash of brandy or Pepsi, whichever he asks.
We no longer force diabetics to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
We brought beer to Mr. H. last night, who died tonight.
In the morning, his son finished this beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help our loved ones as well as our patients,” says Natalie Savard, director of nursing.
At the Victor-Gadbois orphanage, not a single day is like the previous one.
Next to a 93-year-old man, who is enjoying his last meeting with his family in the courtyard, sitting on his pillows during a toast in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children and trying everything to survive.
“In the last six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christian Martel with concern.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois shelter come from home and 47% from the hospital.
The challenge of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, which is the kind of care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients entering the final stage of their life, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor-Gadbois Shelter and the Greater Montreal Palliative Home Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is this large gap in Quebec&#39;s health care system that makes many palliative care physicians fearful of a law that would legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by the luminaries in the field of palliative care, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapuinte, and testifying to their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec&#39;s healthcare system is not effective enough to ensure the right to high quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to relieve them.
I am afraid that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists are trying to save patients until the last day, despite pessimistic forecasts.
Ellen Richard&#39;s survival hopes were already diminishing when she stopped grueling chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regretted that I was stopping the fight, ”she says.
At the same time, she herself told me that my days are numbered!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who ask to die thank the staff for not following their request after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
It should be noted, however, that palliative care is not completely omnipotent in dealing with pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Palliative Home Care Society, patients are non-responsive to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until his death, either from time to time or constantly.
We can no longer pretend that we do not know about this suffering.
Increasingly, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to have access to palliative sedation.
Patients suffering from pain always say the same phrase: &quot;I want to die.&quot;
But this does not necessarily mean &quot;I want to be euthanized&quot;, it means &quot;I want to make it easier for me.&quot;
