Pay and sell without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The exact opposite of current central bank-based monetary exchange, numbered transactions between receiving parties with processing fees.
Also, as is often the case with these technologies, there is a clear political vision: the belief that the current monetary system of banking monopolies is leading to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros ...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows file exchange between peers of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered from 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoin for donation or payment.
Bitcoin, which peaked at $ 30 (23 euros) in June 2011, dropped to $ 2 five months later before returning to about $ 10 today (see bitcoincharts.com for rates).
Nothing fancy compared to the worldwide exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB), in its October virtual currency report, took an interest in the system.
He describes bitcoin as &quot;the most successful virtual currency&quot;, &quot;competing with the dollar or euro&quot; and &quot;similar to conventional currencies.&quot;
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, like &quot;credits&quot; used to promote a video game, which are earned during the game, or which can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by some central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes on the network are simultaneously ledgers, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network function?
Every transaction between two users actually happens between two email addresses, much like an email.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically using a double key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger sent out throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this ledger.
It goes through a math problem sent out to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
It is about the hashing phase of a file, that is, converting a large file into a digital signature that is short and unique.
Computers “take” a new transaction and add a number to it before “hashing” everything together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many leading zeros).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction is thus inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user very quickly (in less than ten minutes) wanted to pay twice with the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solved the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the award is regularly halved, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred million, which leaves still some reserve ...
The complexity of the problem also increases with the increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Bitcoin service sites were attacked and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
&quot;The defect used is not about the protocol itself,&quot; says Pierre Noise, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes real money payments using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also announced the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
Big players like Wikipedia refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute of Science in Israel analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoins never circulate.
The &quot;Giant Sale&quot; was announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmqvist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoin into gold.
Pierre Noise, another author of a tutorial on this currency, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
His system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment through a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which is thus cheaper.
The holder has better control over his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough just to provide an address that can be &quot;photographed and recognized&quot; by a telephone, Pierre Noise specifies, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
&quot;It will take some time for Bitcoin to take hold, but 2013 could be a turning point,&quot; he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, suggests, by the way, to reconsider the various risks that are considered to be elevated today, if this system succeeds.
