Difficult childbirth of the Egyptian Constitution
This is a new risky move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever, over a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, he has decided to play for broke.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
It will soon be two years since Egypt has relied on the preliminary text, which has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal controversy.
This new initiative only strengthened the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his &quot;autocratic delirium&quot;, continuing to &quot;violate the given word&quot; and &quot;trample on the right.&quot;
In the camp of his followers, they are confident that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by speeding up the transition process.
The referendum must be held within fifteen days.
A very short period of time, which makes the Brothers abandon the intention of explaining the text to the Egyptians, article by article.
It is also a way for the president to restore public and democratic legitimacy as discontent rages across the country.
Muhammad Morsy seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in the affirmative, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, the call for an accelerated vote is like an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: &quot;Either you vote for my text, or I reserve myself extraordinary powers,&quot; which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted yesterday in favor of the text.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling unable to convey their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities, or civil society have done the same.
To achieve the required quorum, 11 reserve members were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, in most cases, the articles were voted unanimously.
The commentators were amused by the fact that one of the few controversies of the day had arisen around ... prayer time, as some committee members felt the Constituent Assembly clock was set incorrectly.
The text, which was voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of general attention, article 2 ultimately remained identical to the article from the 1971 Constitution, which stated that “the principles of Sharia are the main source of law”.
Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the main requirements, hoped to replace &quot;principles&quot; with &quot;rules&quot;, which would make it possible to apply them more rigorously.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
&quot;Hypocrisy&quot; - answer the liberals, who see this as only PR.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution occurs through other articles.
They point in particular to Article 220, which grants Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pomier, this is alarming because &quot;the people who are called to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.&quot;
We can observe the birth of a theocracy. &quot;
Many liberals are also agitated by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be much less moderate than the current one.
“There is no specific religious intervention at the moment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulema, but people with a university education, some of them studied in the French system &quot;- reassures Alexis Bloe, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that &quot;ambiguity may arise around Article 220, as the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to &quot;fiqh&quot; [Islamic jurisprudence - ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise as to how competent civil judges are to make decisions about this. &quot;
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday has been criticized because it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they have decreased significantly compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the consideration of the defense budget will take place not in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Nor will it be prohibited to try civilians in military courts, despite requests from human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they consider detrimental to freedom.
Liability for blasphemy has been retained, and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for press freedom.
In addition, none of the articles are talking about protecting women anymore, says Heba Moraef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, the demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will take to the streets on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy places, the Navel of the Earth and the sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and pristine nature.
&quot;AiF&quot; identified five of the most important reasons why you need to visit Israel.
Let us bow down to holy places
It is worth visiting the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that God&#39;s grace descends on everyone who enters this &quot;font&quot;.
And Galilee is the place of Jesus&#39; miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here Jesus appeared before the disciples after his resurrection.
But most of all the shrines are in Jerusalem.
Believers here walk the Way of Sorrow or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin - Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the Anthony fortress - the Pretorium - where the court was, and along the streets of the Old City it leads to the Church of the Holy Sepulcher on Mount Golgotha - to the place of the Crucifixion, the Stone of Anointing and the burial place of Jesus.
There is also a symbolic Christian Navel of the Earth, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was erected on the site where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem, there is also the most holy place for the Jews - the Wailing Wall, left over from the temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different confessions leave notes with wishes here, which are then fulfilled.
Take a vertical trip
The ruins of the Massada fortress remain from a secret refuge from enemies, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC. for your family.
They are located on sheer cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And only those who are fond of mountaineering can get to them on their own.
The rest to this historic peak are taken by a cable car lift.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous ski resort Hermon, where in the winter months there is a huge influx of tourists.
A shuttle bus delivers to it from the foot of the mountain.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an old legend, pagan gods allegedly lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You cannot visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are worth visiting.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains the oldest Qumran manuscripts, or the Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
Its exposition includes paintings of the impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cezanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akko, you can visit the Al Basha Bath Museum, which consists of several halls of ancient Turkish baths with dummies of visitors and bath attendants of that time.
In Caesarea, visit the unique private Rally Museum, where you can admire the sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are not accepted.
The fifth - the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells about one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic section - the children&#39;s memorial - was built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go into it - and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are twinkling.
And the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Get well
Israel&#39;s three main resort areas are located on the coasts of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and aquariums.
Interestingly, people swim in the Red Sea even in the winter months, since the water temperature there does not drop below 21 degrees Celsius, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people swim there all year round.
By the way, this most extraordinary sea in the world is located at the lowest point of the planet - 417 m below ocean level.
The azure water in it is a brine that easily keeps afloat even those who cannot swim at all.
The landscapes around are unrealistically beautiful.
They come here to undergo a course of treatment with the use of salt water - brine, and healing mud, and to cure their health for dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes mellitus, in order to put swaying nerves in order.
Touch the secrets of antiquity
They are kept in the old part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
The famous Sea Route, connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia, passed through it.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists love to wander through the narrow streets named after the signs of the zodiac.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of &quot;your&quot; sign, Fortune will become supportive.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds who come from all over Israel and even other countries for a photo shoot.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can wander around the Roman theater, &quot;take&quot; the fortress of the Crusaders.
During the Roman period, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the seat of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourist notes
Going to Israel, do not worry about your imperfect English: in the country, about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
It is better to take money for a trip not in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily exchanged for shekels (now $ 1 - 3.8 shekels).
Public transport is mostly buses, but Jerusalem has a light rail, and Haifa has the country&#39;s only six-station metro line linking the Lower City to the Upper City.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
Travel in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can travel with changes within 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
Markets, shops and public transport are closed from Friday evening until Saturday sunset.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels, there is only kosher food, excluding pork, seafood, fish without scales, and dishes that combine milk with meat.
They offer a large selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts cooked in coconut milk, traditional Jewish hummus paste, a variety of sauces, ground chickpea balls - falalel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are a lot of well-fed cats that imposingly &quot;walk by themselves.&quot;
In the evening, they can be seen sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Purrs love crowded places and do not refuse treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $ 37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to 188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - $ 15 per day.
Bicycle rental will cost 15 nis. in a day.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
In the language of numbers
In 2012, Israel was visited by over three million tourists from all over the world.
Most of all, citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine came to travel and rest.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the abolition of visas on February 9, 2011.
&quot;Great and mighty&quot; will bring to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While deputies and human rights activists argue about what the law on compulsory language testing will give, fraudsters have already appeared in the country selling &quot;fake&quot; certificates
13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities annually.
For the most part, these are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to support the families left behind.
On December 1, a law came into force, according to which every labor migrant will be obliged to take an exam on knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service sector, housing and communal services, household and retail trade.
However, over time, the FMS promises, the tests will become mandatory for all visitors.
Moreover, you will have to pass not only the language, but also Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Knowledge of the language will have to be confirmed both to obtain and to renew a work permit.
The exception is valid only for citizens of those countries where Russian is the state language.
People who managed to obtain certificates and diplomas of education before the collapse of the USSR in 1991 are also not subject to the law.
Benefit, doom and protection of rights
The network of examination points will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, Peoples&#39; Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants will be able to take tests in all cities; more than 160 such centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce testing was supported by both State Duma deputies and the Federal Migration Service.
But human rights activists, before the law came into force, many times managed to ask the press in the press: what will it actually give?
What will change the obligation to know the language both for Russians and for the visitors themselves?
First of all, - the representatives of the migration service answer, - this will reduce the number of people suffering from &quot;labor slavery&quot;.
A lot of people are now talking about protecting the rights of labor migrants, explains Viktor Sebelev, head of the FMS of Russia in Tajikistan.
The protection of their rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized recruitment system will allow 90% to solve the problems of foreign workers.
Problems appear among migrants without a profession, education, who do not know the language, who do not have a medical examination.
Without understanding the language, - Sebelev is sure, - the future migrant is doomed to face unscrupulous people who, under the guise of help, will stick him in a terrible cramped barrack, where he and dozens of others like him will languish for months without food and documents, injecting 12-14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
&quot;At home they are promised one thing, but upon arrival they are deceived, their passports are taken away, the promised salary is not paid,&quot; confirms Tolib Sharipov, head of the Main Department of Labor Migration of the Ministry of Labor of Tajikistan.
Do not swear, nasyalnik!
Nevertheless, while many citizens of the Central Asian republics who are going to work in Russia, admit that they not only do not know the language of the country they are striving for, but also write with difficulty in their own.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get even a sensible primary education.
After all, their families have nothing to even feed their children with, let alone dress them properly, put on shoes and equip them for school.
Growing up to adolescence, such guys go to work at the first opportunity.
It is difficult, if poorly with knowledge of the language, - they admit.
&quot;You feel humiliated and inferior.&quot;
True, with regard to the language law, human rights defenders note one important point.
Testing will be carried out only for those migrants who have legal status.
If there is no status, there will be no exam or subsequent official work.
Meanwhile, most of the migrant workers still live in Russia illegally.
&quot;Welcome, or No Unauthorized Entry&quot;
Many of the newcomers claim that it is not so easy to obtain official status in our country.
The reason is in bureaucratic obstacles and all the same language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake registration can be done quickly and for only fifteen hundred.
Russian police officers know that we mostly have fake documents, no registration, hence the cases of extortion.
“They ask for a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea,” a citizen of Tajikistan Umed Khushkadamov shared with journalists.
&quot;Come on, don&#39;t be stingy, buy painting&quot;
On the very first day of the entry into force of the language law, it became clear that not only migrant registration documents are fake.
Several &quot;fake&quot; certificates of passing language tests have already been seized by the FMS.
Counterfeit papers are printed on a regular color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get them for nothing: each of the migrants, hoping in this way to make it easier for themselves the task of passing the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than two times more expensive than the official testing procedure: it will cost a labor migrant three thousand.
The authorities and human rights activists agree that the main task for the near future is to protect the system from corruption so that &quot;crusts&quot; cannot be simply bought.
In the meantime, the authorities can promise migrant workers who have not been able to successfully pass the test the first time, time to study a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve active communication with people.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs does not take into circulation the illegal arms market
The share of crimes with the use of legal weapons is extremely small
The Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs proposes to tighten the law against the owners of civilian weapons.
This is the government&#39;s reaction to recent incidents: Press shots at weddings, when there were no casualties, and the massacre staged by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, which killed seven people.
The police want to ban the wearing of traumatics in public places and increase the age from which you can get a license for a weapon - from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption Irina Yarovaya and promised that amendments to the law on weapons would be submitted to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is happy with the fact that the Russian authorities are trying to deal with the problem by &quot;tightening the screws.&quot;
An open letter has appeared on the Internet, the authors of which - representatives of various public shooting organizations - demand that the &quot;senseless tightening&quot; be abandoned.
The percentage of hooliganism with registered weapons is minimal, criminal lawyer Vasily Lesnikov told the BBC Russian Service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Internal Affairs, 142 crimes were committed with the use of firearms registered with the internal affairs bodies in the six months of 2012, while in total 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded during the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that the tightening of legislation in the field of civilian weapons does not prevent the criminal from going to the &quot;black&quot; market.
Now, according to them, in Moscow you can find any weapon at a low price.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry claims that they control the situation with the proliferation of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The &quot;black&quot; arms market is replenished through several channels.
There are five main such channels, says retired colonel Viktor Baranets, who worked for ten years in the structure of the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a site that accepts orders for weapons
The first is the &quot;army or military trail&quot;, that is, weapons that were stolen during the hostilities in the Caucasus.
&quot;The weapons were carried by both Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves,&quot; says Baranets.
The next type of &quot;black weapon&quot; is stolen by criminals from representatives of power structures.
Baranets explains that this includes those carried away from police warehouses and those stolen from directly by law enforcement officers.
Illegal &quot;guns&quot; are sold from military warehouses.
Explosions were frequent in many military depots.
&quot;There are proven versions that some of the arson attacks were made on purpose - to cover up the shortage,&quot; says the former military man.
Weapons manufacturers are making their contribution, according to Barantz.
&quot;Now private arms factories are sprouting, which cannot withstand competition on the international market and are throwing weapons out from under the counter onto the black market, including in Moscow,&quot; the expert says.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
Especially a lot of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, for example, Kyrgyzstan.
&quot;They have their own production, sometimes handicraft, and a mafia was formed, which organized the flow,&quot; explains the former military man.
Where are the weapons from?
Experts have calculated what is the approximate share of each of the sources of supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
A report on this in 2011 was prepared by the Center for Problem Analysis and Public Administration Design.
Experts analyzed the reports of the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Rosstat, criminological literature and open data from portals on weapons.
The overwhelming majority of illegal weapons, the researchers write, come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market ended up there &quot;through the fault of the officials whose work involves weapons,&quot; the report said.
According to researchers, 17% of cases of weapons come from places of armed conflict, in 14% of cases theft occurs at the stage of weapons production, 5% falls on &quot;black archeology&quot;.
