It is not yet clear if this spark will spark the flames of a mass movement.
&quot;So far, deceiving the brain is average.&quot;
Recently, it is customary to perceive the topic of augmented reality, which is popular among fans of modern technologies, mainly through the prism of special glasses.
First, Google showed the current model at its annual conference in the summer, and then in November it became known that Microsoft had also filed an application for the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the group of interactive 3D technologies at the Cambridge laboratory of Microsoft, Sharam Izadi, it follows that for the scientists of this company, glasses are a passed stage.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, creating virtual open spaces.
- Please tell us in general terms what your research group is doing?
- We deal with human interaction with machines, but at the same time we are trying to push the boundaries of this interaction.
While humanity en masse is stuck at the stage of working with pixels on a flat screen, sometimes poking a finger at them.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead and predict radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox today is sold without the Kinect, because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else is ahead of us?
“Even though Kinect has brought interaction to the physical level, a lot still happens on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system is receiving more data), but the output is still not very good.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional display systems based on various technologies, including projective ones.
It is necessary to release the computer world into our physical world, to make it more tangible.
To do this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we will be able to supplement the real world with virtual objects in a much more convenient form.
And first of all - to hell with these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
Popular stuff, but isn&#39;t it overrated?
- It definitely cannot be called a panacea - the question of privacy arises, because you don&#39;t always want to inform others about your actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of interactions with computers are good, but each in its own niche.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not over sweeping ones, but over such mean, short ones.
At the same time, the gestures were filmed not with the device&#39;s camera, but with a wrist bracelet, which recorded the movements of bones and muscles.
While it is large, in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future belongs to a mixed type of control, for example, gesture + voice.
- What is it like?
“For example, how do you ask me to give you this can of soda?
You will say and show at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, it will be very difficult to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot at the moment?
- Not at all necessary, but this is mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will mainly have to work on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to more accurately determine human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, they give a good resolution in depth, this is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your complaints about modern cameras?
Lacking resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what we can build on in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps.
But the point is not in the megapixels themselves, but in the quality of the matrix and depth.
From the latter point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us - this adds work to the algorithm designers.
That is, you need to remember not only about the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also the Z.
Also very important is the speed, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the current 30 fps is frankly not enough, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes from our Redmond laboratory made a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay - from 1 to 100 ms, and modern serial sensors are closer to the second (60-100) indicator.
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between humans and machines.
In my work, the equivalent of such a device would be very useful to me, only it does not require touches, so that there are more frames per second.
- Do you need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three &quot;cameras&quot;, one of which is actually an infrared emitter, and the other is an echo receiver.
And now the third camera is, in fact, an ordinary sensor of the visible range.
It is not used to determine the depth of an object.
Potentially more cameras could solve the problem ...
Or aggravate it by increasing the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible analog of the Kinect, play around with the curvature of the cameras and see how this helps in 3D positioning.
- As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don&#39;t you think that in terms of everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most promising platforms?
- Of course, it&#39;s not very convenient to walk around all the time, holding a smartphone in raised hands, but here&#39;s what I think: the coolest option would be &quot;rolling&quot; augmented reality, when on the basis of a cloud platform you could switch from glasses to a smartphone, a projection display and then everywhere.
Glasses are a very personal device, this is their strength (only you can see private things), and at the same time their weakness - augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let&#39;s imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from &quot;Iron Man&quot;, but also to a mere mortal.
There is one problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tactile feedback!
Hands don&#39;t feel anything!
What responses is your group preparing for this challenge?
- In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth may well be the addition of tactile sensations.
In the meantime, one of the interesting tricks is using the second hand as a kind of background for the image.
She perfectly registers clicks!
But there are technologies that are really aimed at making these &quot;pictures in the air&quot; tangible - for example, the interference of several directed ultrasonic beams at a certain point where the finger is located gives a sensation, but so far it is very weak - as if you were blown on the pads.
There are also wrist bracelets that affect the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he supposedly should feel at the moment when he sees something?
- This is a good idea, we have not tried it yet.
Here lies another task that has to be fought for a long time to come - how to make a person who is physically in a very limited space believe that he is walking along an open, almost infinite - we are also working on the concepts of treadmills (not at all like in clubs) , moving platforms, and huge balls.
While deceiving the brain turns out to be average, there is still a lot of work for many years.
This is what makes working on virtual reality so attractive to the researcher - many things are absolutely rudimentary.
