It follows from this that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, it is necessary to focus on the application of the law itself.
How can this project help you, what does it mean to you?
It is this kind of joint oversight that can contribute to efforts to stop the clarification of laws, and the reduction and improvement of restrictions, because it does not lead to a positive result.
Economics means getting the right thing for a reasonable (but not always low) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
But it is not a fact that we will achieve this by reducing the restriction of orders.
Perhaps this system will overflow with &quot;papers&quot; so that those who wish to find loopholes in this system will find them much easier than if the restriction had not been reduced.
You are talking about internal problems of the practical application of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there such an organization as our KRU (Audit Office) or does it work differently?
As for the institutions, there Bundesrechnungshof acts as our KRU, organized according to our principle, there is also a collegium that works a little differently, but basically both institutions function in the same way.
In addition, the powers are to a certain extent similar, but since Germany has a federal structure, there are audit units at the federal state level - in this their system is somewhat different from ours.
BRH can only manage federal money, we have government funds.
Public funds in our regions and municipalities are controlled at the level of federal accounting chambers.
As for local legislation, is it easier there than ours?
In general, I would not want to compare without specific data, but in some respects Germany can be taken as a model, but one cannot definitely say that it is better in everything.
Is this because they are better at controlling?
Definitely not, but again, I don&#39;t like such comparisons.
But I must say that even model countries face many problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn&#39;t be getting any benefit from working with our office, right?
If we talk about domestic legislation, how did the amendments to the Public Procurement Law affect your institution, are the consequences manifested in some way?
Given that the legal force of these amendments is rather short, it has not yet manifested itself in any way in our control work.
Since we are conducting ex-post control, some delay must be taken into account.
We take this into account only in the process of preparing future audits - we began to use our new tool &quot;uneconomic risk detection&quot;, through which we ran almost 14,000 government contracts. We analyzed them. There, of course, these changes will manifest themselves, because the restrictions change, the conditions of some types of tenders change, and so on.
Do you think the adoption of this law will bring benefits or additional burden on the bureaucratic system?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope this will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise is that the rules will become &quot;stricter&quot; and cannot be followed.
Under the previous rules, controlled enterprises are tied to the supplier (for example, regional operational programs - with the regional council) in that any non-compliance with the public procurement law means a violation of budgetary discipline.
Is it worth it, in this case, to tighten the law in this way?
I think not in this way.
The system should exclude those who want to capture and abuse, but not punish those who make a formal mistake that does not affect the decision.
Such a system will only create even more pressure on the bureaucracy.
And then how to get out of this situation?
Let us be aware that this path will lead nowhere.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the State Traffic Police will not bother entrepreneurs with checks on the so-called Schwarz system. What does it mean?
Is the &quot;Schwarz system&quot; prohibited or allowed?
The law should be established in some way, and if it prohibits something, then the prime minister cannot resist the work of the bodies, which are charged with the duty of checking and enforcing the fulfillment of obligations.
You can say, &quot;We will change this law and allow this,&quot; but you cannot say that we will pretend that nothing is happening.
The Public Procurement Law contains quite strict rules on how and what should be formally carried out, and rightly so. This will protect government procurement.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the candidate with the best offer is disqualified only because of formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly, which, in my opinion, we lack.
