As part of the project for the additional construction of the Jedlichki Institute, a separate building will appear in the future, into which we will move with this project.
Several music groups and performers will perform at each concert.
What were the selection criteria?
We tried to create a program that will interest all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Barta, The Tap Tap, Marjan Bango and Jiri Sukhi will perform in Prague.
All details can be found on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any such &quot;big events&quot; in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring festival and here, of course, we will prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would love to perform at the Czech National House in New York, and personally, if we are in the United States, I would very much like to perform in Washington and Chicago.
As for the foreign countries, you have serious plans, you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you deal with the road in terms of organization and logistics ??
This is not as scary as it seems at first glance.
We have five participants in electric wheelchairs, their wheelchairs must travel in the luggage compartment, plus a large amount of cargo and toolboxes.
Nevertheless, so far they have coped with this without problems. Czech Airlines ČSA and British Airways British Airways have always been excellently prepared for us, which surprised me many times.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to traveling abroad, you can compare different countries in terms of accessibility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities, and so on.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other countries where everything functions better than ours, in Russia we have witnessed that in the east it is still at the basic level.
Compared to Prague, there are a lot of barriers in Moscow, and here it is still a novelty for a person to move independently in an electric wheelchair in the city center.
Also, there are no such banal things as giving way to a disabled person in an elevator.
Fortunately, public organizations are already emerging there that are trying to draw people&#39;s attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what, on the contrary, do we constantly have to catch up with the advanced countries?
There are so many things that are far behind the level of performance.
But it is important to clarify that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the efforts of those people who are concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite normal that people with severe disabilities move independently on the streets, can go to the toilet, to the museum, and anywhere ...
It is not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities take an active part in public life, in this we with The Tap Tap are a little ahead of them!
Respect for the public or disability is one thing, but the moment famous athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers appear among us, then everything really starts to change.
So far, these are isolated cases - people with a strong will.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but going back two years, what made you organize it in 1998?
I entered the Jedlichka Institute as an educator, there were many young people around me who wanted to do something.
And since I am a musician myself and I also play the saxophone, together with a colleague I organized an interesting music club.
Well, over time, as our presenter Ladya Angelovich says, it got a little out of control (laughs).
Popularity has come only in recent years, or am I confusing something?
It’s true, it helped that we started joining famous singers and actively promoting the group.
We came to the conclusion that work that no one can appreciate, in fact, does not seem to exist.
Thanks to the funds of the European Union, we can afford qualified teachers, equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to promote The Tap Tap so well?
From the very beginning, I felt their potential in the ability to do something extraordinary.
Showbiz is full of things that imitate one another.
This is logical, everything new is accepted with caution, and it lasts for a long time.
There are very few rare things out there, but I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us, of course, is pity, this is natural ...
But this pity is completely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not some kind of suffering and all the abandoned individuals that we should feel sorry for.
They are people who can live a fulfilling life and develop, of course, only if they have the necessary resources.
I say that if people with disabilities do something, it is a shift not only for them, but for the whole society.
Has it been successful that you are the strict leader that many believe you are?
