Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the following years took an active part in a number of agency projects.
But Poland began its journey to outer space much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always met with understanding.
Let me remind you, for example, of the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work &quot;Introduction to Cosmonautics&quot; at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Peltry and André Louis Hirsch Prize for &quot;Introduction to Cosmonautics&quot;.
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a well-known world propagandist of cosmonautics, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railroad car equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket should have been used to accelerate or decelerate the cart.
Information about this railcar is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The research was carried out by the Weapons Technology Section in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzycki.
From the surviving materials, it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, work was interrupted.
In 1937, an idea for a photoelectric fighter-rocket appeared in a specialized press, which was proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, and the following year the work &quot;Air torpedo missile and aircraft missile-bomb&quot; by the author Leliva-Kzhivoblotsky was published.
Both projects were developed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were dealt with by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was created in 1937, but after two years of its activity, the work ended due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on astronautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the society was mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal &quot;Problems&quot;, which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would deal with astronautics.
At that time, projects of artificial satellites were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
From the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) tried to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and in the fall, the POA became its full member.
And the next year, the first chairman of the PAA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became deputy chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death, which occurred in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile, capable of covering a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 rocket was tested in the Bledovsky wasteland.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighs about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could cover 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm, and its initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and the Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight range for all three types was 37 km.
In the period between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was being developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a launch weight of 380 kg was capable of launching a payload weighing 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland&#39;s accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Abolishing the public works law is not a solution to the problem.
Last week, a constitutional court overturned the public works law.
The resolution caused a lively discussion in the society.
Undoubtedly, it will be interesting to look at this problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal-oriented economic systems in the EU, as well as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of multiple, unregulated economic competition.
In essence, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and free, unrestricted movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
As a result of the significant difference in the cost of labor (wages), there is price tension.
This concept should be understood as a state when a manufacturer, by delivering a cheap product, tries to withstand economic competition by &quot;knocking down&quot; the cost of a competitor in order to take a large part of the market for himself and, thus, increase his own income.
On a massive scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either the transfer of production abroad, or cheap purchases abroad, or disappearance. As a result, unemployment rises in countries where labor costs are high compared to others.
Since private capital does not bear any social responsibility, including for the unemployment it produces, the inevitable government spending on social needs is growing.
In general, the situation increases the reluctance of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the social economic and social damage caused by them in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that there is no need to provide specific statistics.
The unceremonious methods of private capital create situations at the level of the economies of individual states when the governments of countries are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments leave their own populations to the mercy of private capital, despite social decline.
This is reflected primarily in the changes in the current legislation.
The goal is to economically force their people to submit to the dictates of private capital, primarily in the area of ​​wages.
This acts as a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment and at the same time serves as a tool to curtail the rights of workers in the field of labor law.
As a result, the level of poverty increases, and with it the gap between the poor and the rich.
For several years in the FRG there has been a public distribution of food to the poor, who are unable to feed themselves with their own labor.
The number of these people is already approaching a million.
As part of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are constantly cases when employed people receive such a salary that the state must pay them extra in order for them to receive a living wage.
A similar scandal became known to the public in the case of additional employees of the Bundestag.
Economic measures in almost all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same state in which people, under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in social status, are forced either to emigrate, as it was in the 19th century, or to live on a beggarly salary in the margins of society. in the hope that someday private investment capital will come to the country.
However, the question is, where does it come from?
If capital comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, since Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian, African still work for a share of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media adamantly argue that the state cannot participate in the capital of its own economy, that a managed economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital stubbornly insists that the state should not interfere with the economy by managing its actions.
The next question to be answered is whether private capital, now practically managing politics and the very whole state, is not acting for its own selfish purposes?
The unequivocal answer is yes.
The proof is the existence of almost omnipotent and omnipresent lobbies in all states.
As a result, we have a hopeless situation, manifested in corruption, ensuring mutual benefits, in legislation, where almost everything deserves punishment, but is not a crime.
In Germany, the situation is such that state ministries, due to a lack of financial resources, entrust the development of draft laws to private law firms that are closely associated with industry.
Then these bills are approved by the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as the Western-type constitution says, but from financially powerful groups that prefer their own interests.
Obviously, liberal-oriented democracy is now quickly finding itself in such a situation, as described by Appian in the work &quot;The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Days of Caesar and Pompey&quot;: &quot;The state has long been disintegrating, and the departments are engaged in violence.
Bribery, illegal receipt of favors with stones and swords.
Bribery and corruption flourished without any prohibitions, and people went to the polls with a pre-sold vote &quot;&quot; ... decent people did not run for the post of ruler at all, in the end, one day the state was left without a consul for eight months &quot;..&quot; to say that the only salvation in this terrible situation is autocracy and the need to choose an energetic person &quot;.. Appian thought it would be Pompey, but Caesar became him, who finally changed democracy to autocracy.
As in ancient times, modern society is dominated by its own reckless interests without regard to public interests.
Private capital is no longer inherently intended for public use.
The current result is no different from the past: the unprecedented decline of the elite without any effort to introduce deeper reforms.
This means that we should look for the reason for the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the reckless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
Today, the absence of these regimes and the existence of a liberal type of democracy can be perceived as a certain pause, after which the next round is expected.
First of all, it is tragic that the current elite completely ignores the consequences of hundreds of thousands of victims in the future, the humanitarian and social catastrophes that we are already witnessing, along with crimes against humanity, as we know from old and modern history.
Canceling the public works law is not a solution, or at least not permanently.
Under the pressure of competition at both the international and national and European levels, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
Thus, this trend is systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the share of the state in the economy, strengthen the role of citizens in governing the state and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
