&quot;Operation Argo&quot; Movie: When Worse, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a crowd of Islamist student demonstrators seized the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the ousted Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution in the United States, which had been his regime&#39;s patron for decades.
For the US administration, a positive outcome of the situation was not expected - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because this could fundamentally undermine the confidence of the allies in other countries.
However, she was unable to achieve the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
This was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by a failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released 444 days later, after negotiations brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The defeat in Iran largely contributed to the defeat of Jimmy Carter in the 1980 presidential election, which culminated in the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, &quot;Operation Argo&quot; describes one of the episodes in the story that brought America&#39;s small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After difficult twists and turns, they ended their journey at the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them out of Iran, with the help of an extravagant cover legend, according to which they left with Canadian passports as members of a film crew looking for a location in the country for filming a sci-fi epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, which was devised by &quot;evacuation&quot; expert Tony Mendes, required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the legend true, specialized magazines wrote about the film&#39;s project, held press conferences, and a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck&#39;s film is a special blend of several genres.
On the one hand, there is a real political thriller, the so-called &quot;film-pop&quot;, the story of a successful venture, a swindle - an example is a number of films about Ocean&#39;s friends.
Moods are constantly changing in the film - on the one hand, documented scenes from Tehran (the credits show iconic historical photographs of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lightweight Hollywood clips intersecting with irony and mild exaggeration.
And then more scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in suits discussing the situation at the conference tables, on the stairs of institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck did a wonderful job restarting his career.
From a ridiculed actor he became a respected director, and his acting ceased to be an object of ridicule.
&quot;Operation Argo&quot; is his third feature film, after the dark detective &quot;Goodbye, Baby, Goodbye&quot; (2007) and the thriller &quot;City&quot; (2010).
At the same time, this is Affleck&#39;s first film not filmed in the director&#39;s hometown, Boston.
The sense of the ambience of the place, however, refers to qualities that elevated the director&#39;s earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in “Argo”, where Tehran “plays” Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, reenactments of real events - the opening scenes of the fall of the embassy are impressive in their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when a story suddenly changes somewhere.
Affleck and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake headquarters in a Tehran bazaar).
There are too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes he comes up with something - it all comes out not so elegantly (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents an impending crisis at Tehran airport, and the runway chase looks rather far-fetched).
The disadvantage of &quot;Argo&quot; is the distraction associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are indeed very charming as their Hollywood colleagues, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck&#39;s film lacks a bit of drama, it is a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciating the production and retro style that recreates the thrillers of the seventies.
But it captures with difficulty.
However, this is enough to remind about one, still in a certain sense, living history, as well as to testify to how exaggerated the idea of an omnipotent and all-knowing intelligence services.
Balloon rules, bananas and circus
The portal www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually conducts a survey on the most absurd bank fees, has now decided to announce a competition for &quot;the most absurd regulation or project from the EU workshop.&quot;
“We were prompted to do this by the latest event, in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 percent quota for women in the administration of large European companies,” the organizer of the survey, Patrick Nager, told Pravu.
Among the absurdities already nominated for the nomination is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify the rate of insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, women have had life insurance benefits because they are objectively less at risk for insurance companies.
“Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop people can put forward for the competition before the end of this year.
The voting itself will take place until the end of February 2013, &quot;Nager said.
Controversial EU directives include, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel, which as a result is harmful to nature, as well as a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers just because they contain relatively small amounts of hazardous substances, or a directive on the size of a chicken cage. as a result of which this year eggs have risen in price significantly.
Also criticized was the de facto ban on the use of the term &quot;sandwich butter&quot; or the withdrawal from the sale of classic light bulbs.
Good quality bananas should be 14 centimeters long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes a decision under pressure from one or another trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually protected by some state or group of states (thus, the Czech Republic now, even under threat of veta, defends the demands of its banks).
The interests of the lobby are as follows: for example, the highest quality bananas in the European Union had to reach a length of 14 cm and did not dare to show &quot;anomalous curvature&quot;.
At the same time, the European Commission justified itself by the fact that it was only harmonizing the existing disparate national rules that complicated trade.
The EU, despite the resistance of some states, has nevertheless relaxed the standards regarding fruits and vegetables, citing the fact that the existing directives will lead to waste of products.
Last year&#39;s EU regulation, according to which sold balloons must be warned that children under eight cannot inflate them without adult supervision, may also be a candidate for winning the poll.
The EU turned to US research that balloons play as a potential cause of death by suffocation in children.
A similar restriction now applies to children under the age of 14, who are forbidden to blow on fairground pipes.
Funny ideas are born at home too
The rule concerning the European officials themselves is also quite absurd: everyone who has any official position in the EU cannot, given the delicacy of the topic for Greece, use the name of Macedonia, but must instead say &quot;FYROM&quot; (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia) ...
The Bankovnípoplatky.com portal, in collaboration with the Laissez Faire, an association of liberal economists, proposed for voting, in addition to the above-mentioned absurd rules, for example, the EU rule on the volume of food supplies in the territory of a member state.
The EU has set the maximum amount of food reserves that can be located on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of its accession to the European Union.
Subsequently, the Czech Republic exceeded, for example, the established volumes of canned mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a large fine.
The organizers of the questionnaire were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for the fact that they do not have a sea, and the idea of providing subsidies for applications for subsidies.
But these ideas originated in Prague, not Brussels.
“We are at a disadvantage because we have no sea.
We will ask the European Union for compensation, &quot;said the then Minister of Agriculture Yaroslav Palace (CSDP) in the fall of 2004.
As an argument, he pointed out that the country had a high grain harvest, and as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the state had full warehouses of stocks that needed to be removed.
For the fact that the Czech Republic is far from ports, the EU, according to Palace, had to pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission met the Czech Republic halfway by organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from countries that have no access to the sea.
Subsidies for receiving subsidies were offered to villages by the Ministry of Regional Development, led by Minister Pavel Nemets (US-DEU), in particular, such subsidies were to go to the preparation of an application for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Fancy orders are an exception
While regulations in member states are easily criticized, the EU&#39;s efforts to regulate and to better function and develop the EU are, in the opinion of many experts, deserving of recognition.
A serious problem, according to experts, is the scooping of EU subsidies for projects that do not even have a hint of anything to do with deepening European integration, but which the member states achieved when discussing the budget.
It also evokes emotions among Czechs that, like in other EU countries, the Czech Republic must fight in Brussels for the right to a specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win in this competition.
Although the Czechs, after six years of fighting with the Germans and Austrians, retained the name &quot;Olomouc cheese&quot;, however, &quot;Tuzemsky rum&quot;, whose traditions in our country go back to the 19th century, our producers had to rename to &quot;Tuzemak&quot;.
Only products made from cane distillate, not from sugar beets, can be called rum.
Along with the world famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from German Lübeck or Parma ham, the official list of EU registered products includes, for example, Karlovy Vary rusks, Pogorzelice and Třeboонь carp and atec hops.
Pardubice gingerbread and mustache rolls can also be proud of the EU trademark.
