MVRDV architects prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - with Speikenisse and his newly built Book Mountain as an example - 2 photos
“I find this building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally we can see something interesting again,” says Lisette Verheig, a passer-by at the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, says: &quot;No, this building is really beautiful.&quot;
But I ask myself: why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad, and e-books.
Nowadays, no one volunteers to go to such old-fashioned libraries, right?
Speikenisse, an unremarkable bedroom town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest educational level in the Netherlands.
To combat this annoying circumstance, several years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesquely painted reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And then the city fathers realized that they had the only opportunity to overcome statistics: to build a library here!
Winnie Maas of the MVRDV architecture firm in Rotterdam, a master of bold bar charts and author of witty, sometimes even cynical constructions, took the task with his usual equanimity and appeared at the competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smirk on his face.
And while the members of the jury looked around in bewilderment and shrugged their shoulders, the impudent Maas folded a pyramid in size from his original gift and ended his speech in defense of his project with the following words: &quot;Dear citizens!&quot;
This is my proposal: &quot;Book Mountain&quot; in Speikeniss, the so-called Buckenberg!
Nine years later, this 30 million euro mountain has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground garage, supermarket, post office and several adjacent residential buildings and townhouses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, &quot;Book Mountain&quot; was awarded the second prize in the &quot;Best Library of the Netherlands 2012&quot; competition.
The project also participates in the 2012 Dutch national timber construction competition.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which previously could offer nothing but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, whose white facades suggest a dairy, has become richer by one modern piece of architecture.
But the most important thing is that the first public cultural building in the history of this town appeared in Speikeniss.
Long road to the book
First impression: a bookish Eldorado under a cheese hood.
There is only one elevator in the center of the mountain range, because true fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glazed on all sides, the space is bright and easy to see, with baked brick floors and elegant street lamps that unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfectly recreated.
The look involuntarily searches for benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
&quot;Usually there are bookshelves along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark room, usually uncomfortable and impersonal,&quot; says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic space configuration upside down and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The interior space of the Book Mountain is skillfully used: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical rooms.
Particularly pleasing are the black bookshelves, which serve as wall decoration, parapets, or stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and civil engineers are at a loss as to what this unknown material is.
“We were keen to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trauborst, project manager for the Speikenisse community, in line with the standard.
And once, at an agricultural enterprise in Friesland, we came across a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years, greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands have been using millimeter-thick synthetic fiber material as root liners.
It&#39;s cheap and time-saving.
Thin textiles last one or two seasons, after which they can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was pressed into panels four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material that smells a bit like a new car and a little sneakers.
105 steps lead to the top.
Anyone who overcomes the path of almost 500 meters will be rewarded in the literary cafe not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted tree figs.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all about the correct air humidity on the literary mountain.
The cost of a new soul
“It&#39;s hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trowborst.
The heat of the earth is used to heat and cool it.
Although the Book Mountain stands under a glass cover, even on clear days the sun gets inside only for a short time.
Wide laminated timber trusses perpendicular to the glass façade provide shade and absorb most of the sun&#39;s rays.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned IT skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verheig was already here.
And also the teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogard, who called Buckenberg &quot;the soul of Speikenisse, which has been lacking for a long time.&quot;
Reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from their own collection.
These books were supposed to take up empty spaces on the shelves of the not yet fully stocked library - at that time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
The shelves are packed to the top.
&quot;There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,&quot; says architect Winy Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident is now connected in some way with this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it is only for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal problem, which in professional jargon is called identity creation.
Speikenisse wrote his literary history.
And even if they are very young and uneducated.
After all, this is only the starting point for building an identity.
Szabo: &quot;Germans must play a more important role&quot;
Germany abstained in the vote to recognize Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, in doing so, Berlin is teetering on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany first signaled that it would vote against the Palestinians&#39; application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from voting.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support the actions of the Israelis in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that she also does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained from voting on the no-fly zone.
As a result, NATO passed the proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, it is moving from a policy that, so to speak, ruled by the United States, to German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that the Europeans do not have an agreed common policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that while they are only groping for their role, they are on the way to a &quot;more normal&quot; foreign policy.
Such a foreign policy as France or Great Britain is pursuing.
What exactly does &quot;normal&quot; foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position in their national interests that does not depend on the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and connections with certain regions such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany&#39;s economic interests are largely different from those of other large states, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position in the Middle East conflict and the voting in the UN?
First, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, in particular in the Gulf states.
