Sexually Transmitted Infection Facts
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes, and hepatitis.
Pubic lice and scabies are parasitic STIs.
What are the main target groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydial infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea, and human papilloma virus.
HIV prevalence among heterosexual adults is relatively low in our country - but about 20 percent of new HIV infections are in this group.
Chlamydial infections are much more common among young people than among other population groups.
According to European data, three quarters of all infections affect young people between 15 and 25 years old.
Human papilloma virus is also common among our youth.
How is the number of infections changing?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory registration.
The incidence of syphilis has more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011, according to the Robert Koch Institute.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This is about one-tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases may cause ulcers in the genital area, complaints during urination, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, as well as blisters or lumps.
However, they are often not accompanied by pain or other symptoms and go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not provide 100% protection.
Indeed, in part, the causative agents of sexually transmitted diseases can also be spread by contact infection and through close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular check-ups, especially if you frequently change sexual partners.
With early diagnosis, most STIs can be cured and long-term consequences avoided.
