After all, all of them, until now hopelessly divided in the confused opposition, are in fear.
Fear of a religious state on the Nile at the mercy of the powerful Muslim Brotherhood.
Mohammed Morsi, almost apologizing, said that he temporarily curtailed the competence of the constitutional court and expanded its competence &quot;to save the revolution.&quot;
However, what the 61-year-old engineer with a doctorate from the American University of Southern California actually wants to save is not entirely clear to the Egyptians and the world.
Will the judiciary be nullified?
In fact, 234 articles managed to get through in a 15-hour obstacle race overnight at an Islamist-minded 100-member constitutional assembly, and this is partly a matter of concern.
As in previous constitutions, the draft states that the legal procedure is based on &quot;the principles of Islamic law.&quot;
But what do &quot;principles&quot; mean?
This was and remains a matter of interpretation, and it is feared that the Islamists will use the vague wording and the resulting legal backlash to reinterpret the Sharia law.
At least this is hinted at in one newly introduced article: in all matters concerning Sharia law, Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamic institution in the country, with great authority in all Sunni Islam, should be involved for the council.
This should not, but may mean that the clergy oversees the legislation, which, de facto, would have the effect of limiting the judiciary.
Much is the subject of interpretation in the draft constitution
Another problem: the jurisdiction of civilians to a military court must remain.
These courts during the Mubarak period served to suppress the opposition.
After the overthrow of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were in military custody.
Also, as stated in the draft, the state must protect the &quot;true essence of the Egyptian family&quot; and &quot;uphold its morality and values.&quot;
Legally, this is formulated so vaguely that state institutions with the help of this article will be able to control even the content of films and literature.
In plain text, this means nothing more than censorship.
In general, not a single article directly establishes equality between men and women.
But the other forbids insulting and denigrating the Prophet Muhammad and his messengers.
But what an insult is and how it should be punished remains unclear.
The wording that “offending people” is prohibited is also doubtful.
Will a cartoon of the president or a joke about a jurist be enough?
A question of interpretation, like much in this draft, which Morsi is proposing for signature and which, in his words, &quot;very soon&quot; will be submitted to the Egyptians for a referendum.
&quot;The revolution is back&quot;
For several weeks now, opposition has been forming against the superiority of the Islamists.
Tens of thousands of people gathered in extraordinary unanimity on Friday night in Tahrir Square in Cairo and vowed to destroy the document before it can take effect.
&quot;The revolution is back and we will win,&quot; said Hamdin Sabbahi, who came in third in the presidential election.
Mohammed ElBaradei, Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former head of the international atomic energy agency, said that the draft constitution belongs to &quot;the dustbin of history.&quot;
Through Twitter, he accused Morsi supporters of wanting to spearhead a &quot;coup against democracy.&quot;
&quot;If he announces a referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him,&quot; said opposition leader Yasser Said.
&quot;We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been avenged,&quot; the Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Khaled Ali as saying.
Many judges also indicated that they did not want to observe the referendum, which would invalidate it.
&quot;The Koran is our constitution&quot;
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, in turn, called for the opposite demonstration, but, as a precaution, not in Tahrir Square, but after mass prayer on the other side of the Nile in front of Cairo University.
It was attended by a large number of veiled women and adherents of the Salafis, who shouted: &quot;The people demand the application of God&#39;s law.&quot;
They demanded from Mursi: &quot;Cleanse the country!&quot; and assured: &quot;The Koran is our constitution.&quot;
The struggle for power over the symbolic square, where it all began, provoked a state of almost civil war.
The followers of Morsi, quite obviously, did not want to take this risk.
The Muslim Brotherhood said that both opponents and supporters of the draft constitution spoke loudly and clearly.
Now is the time to let the people decide at the ballot box which direction the country should take.
Most are for the Islamists&#39; project, it is considered a settled matter.
&quot;The concept of&quot; human rights &quot;is never mentioned&quot;
Hafiz Abu Sayed is furious at this forced constitutional process, which, in fact, was supposed to last until February with the participation of all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EHRO) defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were imprisoned or put on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he shared their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible for him.
For this he was beaten, sentenced, arrested.
And now the words &quot;human rights&quot; are never found in the new constitution, he regrets in an interview with &quot;Welt am Sonntag&quot;.
The expansion of Mursi&#39;s influence on all three branches of government in the state disappoints the lawyer.
These measures represent clear blows to the democratic rules of the game and will lead the Egyptians to a new dictatorship.
&quot;Instead of strengthening the civil state, the president de facto annulled it,&quot; Saeda regrets.
After all, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Sayeda feels that everyone has left him, even the international community, which looks at the ideological struggle of directions on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
For this, retribution may come.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: &quot;You are creating a monster that you cannot control.&quot;
Norwegian rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
Norway&#39;s 5 million people have one of the highest living standards not only in Europe but throughout the world.
Perhaps the secret of this country&#39;s success has something to do with a local addiction to one extremely offensive fish dish?
Take some overripe cheese chunks.
Put them in a pile of dirty and sweaty sportswear.
Leave them there for a week.
The smell of rakfisk, one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies, will be created for you.
I am in a small town called Fagernes, three hours from Oslo.
Scenic views covered with snow all around. It is very beautiful, but there is an indestructible characteristic smell in the air.
Rakfisk is a trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for up to a year, depending on what kind of sweetness you want to achieve.
As dusk deepens and colder, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes dedicated to this very, shall we say, exciting dish.
“It is eaten raw and washed down with a glass of aquavit, the local caraway vodka,” explains Haward Halvarsen, a local firefighter and Rakfisk general who runs the festival.
All around us, people eat fish cut into small cubes and wash it down with large drinks.
“Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk,” says Howard.
This drink is able to kill the smell.
I&#39;m trying a couple of bites.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - not much different from the portion of sushi that you took with you on the bus for a long time.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from a completely different era, a time of poverty, when, even before the advent of refrigerators, fish was soaked in hermetically sealed barrels of salt water in the fall.
Then, in deep winter, when the fish was already well and thoroughly fermented, it was taken out and, muffling its perception with alcohol, was eaten.
The last generation remembers the fact that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly to the USA.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants who are attracted here by jobs, high wages and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (a longtime rival, and not so long ago and a much more prosperous neighbor) come here to work en masse.
Rakfisk is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat fetid element of Norway&#39;s past.
This is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will set you back £ 9 ($ 14).
Norway rarely makes headlines in the world, and most people in the country seem to be fine with it.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, the racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the terrorist attack is called &quot;what happened on July 22nd.&quot;
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
At the heart of Norway&#39;s prosperity today is the growth (since the early seventies) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“But oil is not the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our waitress serving trays of seasoned rakfisk, a woman with long blonde hair and striking blue eyes, the epitome of Nordic well-being.
We are such a people - as you call it - reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks excellent English.
We do not like to be shown, we are not boastful.
Norway is very careful with its oil - most of the revenues of the oil and gas industry are invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone wasted money they didn’t have, Norway was careful to calculate all costs.
&quot;As long as you can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, that&#39;s enough for happiness,&quot; says Anna.
“And there is rakfisk,” she adds with a carefree laugh.
I&#39;m standing in the snow in line for some food - I&#39;ve had enough of Rakfisk.
Here is a hamburger with moose meat - this is certainly exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell awaits us.
I have a special rakfisk dinner at my hotel, where visitors vote on the best or perhaps the most flavorful fish.
There is a live TV broadcast, in which they show the host in a bow tie, surrounded by plates with rakfisk.
It&#39;s like the Eurovision Song Contest.
&quot;So, Thor-Jurgen, what grade did you give for the best fish out there in your mountains?&quot;
&quot;Yes, Howard, here&#39;s our score.&quot;
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls out of the chair, possibly after going over the aquavit.
Or maybe just breathing in the smell of this fish.
Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto will have a difficult career start.
As new Mexican President-elect Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC reporter Will Grant invites us to look at the challenges he will face and the mixed expectations of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is currently in a particularly dire state.
This city is congested with transport and at the best of times, and since Monday, steel barriers have been erected, cutting off several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will don the presidential sling and take the reins of the country.
He faces a daunting task.
Mexico has enjoyed good economic performance under the now resigning administration of Felipe Calderón, but the country is mired in a war on drugs that has claimed nearly 60,000 lives in six years.
“My government is declaring to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence,” Mr. Peña Nieto told US President Barack Obama earlier this week in the White House Oval Office.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Prior to such statements, alongside the President of the United States, Mr. Peña Nieto&#39;s political career developed as governor of his home state of Mexico City.
In his homeland, in a densely populated and sprawling state that surrounds the country&#39;s capital, opinions were divided about the new leader.
Straightforward person
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, it is fondly remembered.
Residents credit him with the revitalization of tourism, the development of the resort sector and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached via one of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which are strikingly different from the potholed and pit roads that were previously on this site.
Placards with his name hang on the modern sports center building and on the impressive interactive climate change museum.
&quot;We are pinning our hopes on him for real and meaningful change,&quot; says his friend and political ally Gabrielle Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman from the Pena Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We expect real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed by our country, primarily in the field of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI party was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Peña Nieto.
In addition, he denies the accusations of lack of content, which the opposition has put forward to the new president.
He is very straightforward and very dedicated to realizing his vision of the country&#39;s future.
This is an excellent statesman, and, above all, a person who knows how to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nes, is in stark contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden underneath highways, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also severe in this metropolis.
Earlier this year, troops were brought in to tame drug gangs in these areas; and violence against women is particularly acute here.
In a vacant lot near a vast dump, several dozen bodies of murdered women have been found in the last two years alone.
More than a thousand women were killed in Mexico City during the governorship of Mr. Peña Nieto, far more than in the notoriously violent city of Ciudad Juarez, which has become a household name when it comes to the murder of innocent women.
According to opponents of Mr. Peña Nieto, at best it can be said about him that during his tenure as governor, he was unable to cope with the problem of the murder of women.
In the worst case, his administration is accused of completely ignoring the problem.
A resident of a concrete house similar to most of the houses in this dilapidated area, Irenéa Buendia can hardly hold back her tears as she shows me photographs of her late daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner killed her.
“When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed before,” Ms Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she had been beaten and her body was already numb.
Mariana&#39;s mother retells this story, and her daughter&#39;s portrait looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to the crucifix, on which is inscribed just one word: justice.
It was this, they said, that this family was denied.
&quot;State officials treated me like an old gossip, a disgruntled troublemaker.
They want people to just take what they say on faith and keep quiet.
But it’s wrong, it’s impossible, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around, ”she says.
Donning the presidential sling on Saturday, President Peña Nieto will take on a difficult responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crimes, and the new president has pledged to prioritize addressing the issue during his tenure.
“I hope he will be exactly the same president as he was governor,” says Olvera, a PRI congressman from Valle de Bravo.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nes fear most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of mistreatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning&#39;s claims of poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Manning&#39;s stay at the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is demanding that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning&#39;s conditions of detention were harsh.
A private in the US Army is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest classified leaks in U.S. history, did not take advantage of multiple opportunities to file a complaint about the ill-treatment he said he endured while in a military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Ashden Fein stated that records of Manning&#39;s weekly visits by prison officials during his nine months in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the defense motion to discontinue Manning&#39;s case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were harsh and in themselves punishment enough was carried out the day after Manning stated that while in custody he intended to commit suicide ...
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet by the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday&#39;s hearing, Attorney Fein, along with Manning, reviewed the reports that were filled out following visits to Manning by officials during his time in Quantico Prison, where he was held under strict conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he rated himself as &quot;excellent&quot; by the prison administration and the general conditions of detention as &quot;very professionally organized.&quot;
The reports reviewed did not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being directly asked about his conditions of detention, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed verbal concern about the problems and that the administration officials who visited him discussed the problems with him and said that they would be dealt with, but did not write it down.
&quot;They wrote down &#39;no issues&#39; (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn&#39;t mean I didn&#39;t bring it up in the conversation,&quot; says Manning.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lindh, also asked Manning why he didn’t complain about his ill-treatment in January 2011 during a committee meeting considering suicidal intentions, which he had expressed in writing several months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting, he wanted to get him removed from the &quot;injury prevention&quot; regime and relaxed conditions of detention.
The military officials explained that the restricted detention regime - one level lower than the supervision regime to prevent suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner as well as for the safety of others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that I’m okay, so that they can remove the injury prevention regime ... so that my level of life improves, from my point of view,” explained Manning.
Manning testified Thursday of his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at the Naval Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait and that one day he passed out due to extreme heat.
He explained that psychologically it is very difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is being decided and what is happening in the outside world.
&quot;My world has shrunk to the Camp Arifjan base, to the size of my prison,&quot; Manning said Thursday.
&quot;I thought I was going to die in this cage.&quot;
While in Quantico, Manning, he says, spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day - all alone.
Manning says he was only allowed to keep a mattress, blanket, slippers, a few pieces of clothing, and glasses.
He says that he tried to move, since sleeping or even just lying in the daytime was forbidden by the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, light from outside the cell was constantly hitting his eyes.
If the guards did not see his face when he rolled over in bed at night, then, according to him, he was woken up and forced to turn over on his back.
Manning&#39;s lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning&#39;s ill-treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about a statement he made during his Thursday testimony that after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates. at the morning check.
Manning stated that he was not able to cover himself with a blanket during the check.
Answering the judge&#39;s questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard&#39;s order that he should throw a blanket to cover himself, but admitted that no one had explicitly ordered him to throw it.
Manning said Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night due to his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said that he told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his panties or slippers to injure himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he went through during his detention and significantly reduce the sentence if Manning is found guilty by a military court, which is to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to invite Manning to plead guilty for less serious crimes, and dispute other charges as excessive.
The resumption of the hearings is scheduled for this weekend, with the prosecution expected to insist that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico under the highest security rules.
Charges leveled at Manning include aiding the enemy, illegally facilitating the release of data on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and stealing government property or documents.
If convicted on all counts of the indictment, he could face life imprisonment.
My Crisis of National Identity is the story of a Mexican American.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the country about difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that American Mexicans are torn between the two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrivals corridor, approached the border control area, and froze in place.
The signs indicated two lines: one for the Mexicanos (Mexicans), the other for the Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for several seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California and have been called Mexican all my life.
It&#39;s just a shorthand name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York call themselves Italians.
Later, I settled on the intricate construction of &quot;Mexican American&quot;.
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather&#39;s homeland, there was no need for conventional names or complex structures.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask or answer questions.
But my vocabulary is poorer than native speakers, and I can&#39;t get rid of my American accent.
So I took out my American passport and stood in line for the Extranjeros.
I recalled this story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The agenda included issues familiar to the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Peña Nieto has been eager to talk about a boom in the Mexican economy that will allow Mexicans to now just as well stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a kind of North American trading bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and resentful question.
It never occurred to most Americans that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced its leaders at gunpoint to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only necessary for any US statesman to say a word of criticism towards Mexico, the press and among the elite of Mexican society immediately hear complaints that the Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are filled with militancy.
The most difficult is Mexico&#39;s relationship with more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about grudges?
There are enough of them.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio there are so many people of Mexican descent for one reason only: at some point in their family history, anyone - a father or a grandfather - did not have the opportunity to realize themselves in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often these were Mexicans of a certain type - swarthy, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember this.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we went to good schools and got good jobs, but we must not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and unclear, but we know which country to consider ours.
United States of America.
Plus, we know that most of the Mexican elite and ruling class don&#39;t like us.
We answer them in kind.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us like second-class people, like fake Mexicans.
We do not speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is due to failure.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We would not find ourselves behind the silk curtain now, finding a well-fed life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain tensions between real Mexicans and Mexican Americans - Mexicans have a better understanding of their national identity, while Mexican Americans are offended.
She is a US citizen and believes she belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many of the Mexican Americans I know don&#39;t feel like they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
And in the USA we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relationship is not already tangled enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican Americans to act as ambassadors for Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends how wonderful this country is and how great it is to visit, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah of course.
Nothing will come of it.
Too many grievances in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful at all.
Sorry, but deal with this yourself, amigos.
And this is true.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what it did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican Americans are still resentful about how their relatives were treated in Mexico recently. ...
Yeah.
Perhaps we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
Ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas may provide fragile foundation for further peace
Is Lasting Peace Possible Between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed pushes one to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
The habitual, senseless arguments about who started first are heard; many buildings have been turned into ruins; over 140 Palestinians, most of whom were civilians, and six Israelis killed; for the first time during the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip fell in the vicinity of the Israeli capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly bogged down in their age-old conflict, change has come to the Middle East.
This can be viewed in different ways, but the events of the &quot;Arab Spring&quot; swirled a lot of established realities in a rebellious storm, and the Palestinians and the Israelis did not manage to stay away from the whirlwind that shook the region.
Perhaps as a result, their fight will become even bloodier than before.
However, there are reasons that give hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
War without winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give grounds for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, is carried out, this week&#39;s clashes have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist movement Hamas, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will argue that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the leaders of the group were killed, and 1.7 million people were trapped in one of the most densely populated and problem areas of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that time is on their side.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and wealthy friends.
A resurgent regional leader Turkey, once Israel&#39;s closest Muslim ally, has come out in support of Hamas; Qatar, one of the richest and dynamically developing states of the Persian Gulf, followed its example.
Triumphant Hamas supporters claim the creation of an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, ruled by the paramilitary Hezbollah, to Syria, in which increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow the rule of Bashar Assad, and on to Jordan, where the king&#39;s power is threatened by allies Hamas.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on Israel&#39;s southern borders, the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened under President Mohammad Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was ousted in 2011, was a secular dictator with little emphasis on supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization much like Hamas, and their leaders are more populist.
In future diplomatic constellations, Hamas may become a significant player, whose voice even Israel and America will not be able to drown out.
At the same time, hardliners in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
Militarily, Hamas was defeated.
Israel&#39;s Iron Dome anti-missile system has justified the cost of its development and has successfully destroyed many of the missiles launched by Hamas.
Israeli citizens can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, the United States has remained true to its unchanged position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for starting the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004 about 30 Israelis have died from rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part by the wall that extends into the West Bank, a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian states - and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions from the point of view of international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu&#39;s position, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is quite convenient.
What is the point of pandering to the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If you put all power in the West Bank into their hands, will they not start firing rockets from there towards Israel, as their brothers in the Gaza Strip do?
Better to keep them behind a wall and firmly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will prevail; however, their calculations can be refuted by the Arab spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, internal problems will become their priority.
Israel&#39;s defense budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Unleashing a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments bolster their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on the ceasefire, is a good sign and could herald the beginning of change.
Israel, no less, must consider the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change takes place in Arab countries, stripping Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a ticking time bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining the foundations of a democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement come at a price with growing international discontent.
Both sides need external impetus
There remains the only solution that sane representatives on both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper, are relentlessly calling for: the formation of two states and the cession of territories by Israel in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not very impressive in the short term - the hope that a ceasefire will allow other countries to more effectively influence the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, which is long overdue to decide to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, and Turkey and Qatar are more than ever positioned to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state, adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming vote in the UN, which could result in the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama must also play a role in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he continues to demonstrate a reluctance to get involved in solving this problem.
This is a disastrously short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible in the event of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australia has enacted a uniform packaging law for cigarettes.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of diseased body parts stand out in contrast on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The world&#39;s first Australian law on the same type of packaging for cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color design of different brands with the same dull olive box with creepy pictures of diseased body parts and images of children whose health was undermined by their parents&#39; smoking.
Apart from various pictures and inscriptions warning about the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs, introduced without fail this Saturday, is the names of stamps, which are printed in the same small print.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for the packaging of tobacco products.
The Australian federal government says the goal of this measure is to keep young people from smoking by stripping the habit of fashionable status.
This decision was based on the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26, in 99 cases out of 100, never become smokers.
“It is obvious that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging design,” explains Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, a crown in a logo is associated in children with the idea of a princess. ...
Australia is one of the countries with the smallest smokers in the world, so these changes will not greatly affect the profits of multinationals, but other countries are already considering taking similar measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the passage of this law.
The tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the black market share of cheap and affordable cigarettes.
&quot;This law will have serious consequences different from those envisioned by its initiators,&quot; said Scott McIntyre, British American Tobacco Representative in Australia.
Counterfeiters in China and Indonesia will supply many more of these items to sell on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the other hand, new laws are driving business growth.
Sandra Ha of a small family-owned company, Zico Import Pty Ltd, argues that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone cases that hide unpleasant pictures on the packaging has skyrocketed (practically from scratch) since two months ago such companies as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost their case in the Australian high court, where they tried to appeal against the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 products to wholesalers and is expecting a new batch.
This is good business for us.
A potential hindrance to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the very segment of the population to which these measures are directed.
Following the passage of a series of laws in Australia that made it illegal to advertise cigarettes on television and support sporting events, and prohibit sellers from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local businesses and websites from advertising online, but it cannot restrict overseas sites from doing so.
&quot;If you are a tobacco dealer and you have only this small loophole left, the idea of promoting your product on the Internet will be very tempting for you,&quot; explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of brand reviews written in the name of supposedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is this really the handiwork of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spared no effort and time and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind it?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry is now more busy adapting to new regulations than advertising.
Representatives of the tobacco industry have even gone to measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states are making claims within the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade was unfairly restricted, despite the fact that trade relations of all these countries with Australia are very small.
A WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plibersek, the government has discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory posting of photographs warning about the dangers of smoking.
Now this rule has been adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of stricter laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia defiantly disobey innovation.
These pictures don&#39;t bother me.
I just don&#39;t pay attention.
“You just grab a cigarette and put the pack in your pocket,” explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a photo of an oral tumor on the pack.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me quit is my little daughter.
James Yoo, manager of King of the Pack tobacconists in downtown Sydney, says the same packaging made it harder to place items on the shelves.
&quot;It used to take me an hour to unload a new batch, but now it&#39;s four hours,&quot; he complains.
&quot;The government should have taken and completely banned cigarettes, then we would have said: what to do, okay, it&#39;s all over, we are closing the store,&quot; he says, throwing up his hands.
Getting bored in the world of electronic grids and constant connections is not so bad.
On this Thanksgiving Day, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had a mechanical problem and was replaced by another plane that we were waiting for.
This gave me plenty of time to reflect on the nature of boredom.
I will not deceive you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for your flight is really boring, and books, magazines, iPhones, or even duty-free shops will not help much.
Recently, however, an increasing number of scientists and child development specialists have spoken out in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations, it is not so bad for us and for our children to be bored.
This forces the brain to be distracted by interesting, related topics, which may be conducive to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some kind of screen, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we need to strive for boredom?
Yes.
And at the same time, no.
We will come back to this later.
Previously, I, like many, believed that boredom was an invention of relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of The Fascinating History of Boredom (Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011).
“In fact, boredom has a very ancient history,” he says.
On the walls in Pompeii, Latin inscriptions about boredom dating from the first century are found.
This leaves open the question of how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has changed frequently.
After reviewing the research material on this topic and asking a question of a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people &quot;want but cannot do something that would bring them satisfaction.&quot;
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person isn&#39;t doing something they would like to do.
With apathy, you don&#39;t want to do anything.
The main thing in the boredom experienced, he says, is &quot;a disturbance in attention and the associated deterioration in mood and the feeling that time is passing slowly.&quot;
Boredom can seem a lot like depression when described.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these states, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel like we are bored when in reality it is simply difficult for us to concentrate on something.
In their study, The Idle Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention, published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading the magazine.
Some participants also heard the loud sounds of an irrelevant TV program playing in the next room, others heard the same sounds at a low volume so that they could hardly be heard, and the third group listened only to the voice recording without extraneous soundtrack.
Those participants who heard the TV at low volume noted that they were bored, more often than others - it was difficult for them to concentrate, but they did not know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we&#39;re trying to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interruptions can cause boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, &quot;for example, peering into the flow of products on an assembly line in search of defects, distracting music can help to avoid boredom.&quot;
It is believed, he continues, that when people start to sway in a chair or draw scribbles on a piece of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that in fact, such actions simply help not to relax physically.
&quot;The study showed that children who are not prohibited from fidgeting and spinning, learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit still,&quot; says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we all experience boredom: when the flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people show different degrees of boredom tendencies.
In the 1980s, researchers developed a &quot;Boredom Propensity Scale&quot; to measure these individual characteristics.
This scale uses questions and statements such as &quot;Much of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous&quot; or &quot;I am interested in too many things, so there is not enough time for anything.&quot;
Using these questionnaires, researchers have determined that boys are more likely to be bored than girls, ”says Stephen Wodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida,“ especially in the presence of a variety of external stimuli.
In general, however, teenagers are often bored in general.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he paged almost 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day.
He got the following results: 32% of teens said they were bored at school and while doing homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
At the same time, only 3% of parents noted that they are bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what similar data on boredom would be now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that &quot;adolescence is the peak of the tendency to boredom,&quot; mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Back to my original question: is boredom good for you?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, studies show that it can push people into absurd and dangerous physical activities, risky gambling or the abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have pondered the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has devoted more than two decades to studying the problem.
&quot;This is how our brains tell us to do something else; that&#39;s boredom,&quot; says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at New York University.
However, this very brain does not always know what exactly is better to do.
If you get bored and channel that energy into guitar playing or culinary experiences, you will make yourself better.
However, if you watch TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop bored, but he will not learn to deal with boredom on his own or in any other way to manage his time and employment, says Professor Fenske.
“And these self-regulatory skills are used in a wide variety of situations,” he says.
Your child not only learns to keep himself occupied with something, he also learns to self-control in general.
I don&#39;t think boredom should be extolled in any way.
However, it is not worth considering it as something bad either.
Rather, one should learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous stream of action and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“We see it in such a way that we need to feel bored more often, while boredom is an extremely unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
&quot;In today&#39;s world, we are used to constantly overstimulating our senses,&quot; he says, &quot;and when there is silence, we get lost and don&#39;t know what to do.&quot;
It is not yet clear how Colorado&#39;s new marijuana law will be enforced.
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old soccer player and community college student in southeastern Colorado, is charged with a felony of what will soon be perfectly legal throughout the state: possession of a small batch of marijuana and a pipe in which he smoked it.
Mr. Orozco says he was in Lamar with friends one September, driving along the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer found marijuana in his car, Mr. Orozco received a subpoena for possession of drugs and possession of a drug-using device - minor offenses, each with a $ 100 fine - and a court date.
“We are treated like criminals,” says Mr. Orozco.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that has been going on for weeks after the state of Colorado voted to legalize the use of marijuana in small quantities for entertainment, hundreds of small court cases depend not so much on the law as on the location.
Petty marijuana charges are already being dropped in hundreds of cases here and in Washington state, which has taken a similar action.
Police stations have already stopped charging people 21 and older for possession of small doses, which will become legal as soon as the law goes into effect in a couple of weeks.
However, in the more conservative counties of Colorado, prosecutors have decided to try existing marijuana cases and are still being prosecuted for possession of the drug.
At the same time, cities from the Denver suburbs to the highlands of the West are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from entering their locations.
&quot;This is all progressing so fast that I don&#39;t even know what to expect next,&quot; says Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in the town of Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulatory officials in Washington state are also scratching their heads in puzzlement.
They will have to formulate rules to determine the licensing procedure for the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done by December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most other states in dealing with marijuana use, first for medical purposes and now for entertainment.
&quot;Colorado has a more orderly market, so they are a good example,&quot; said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Alcoholic Beverages Regulatory Board.
But now, no one can do more, Mr. Smith admits, than put forward some suggestions and hope it works.
“We have no real precedent to guide us,” he says.
The Washington state bill, dubbed I-502, will go into effect on December 6 and will leave the state in a state of uncertainty for a full year, when there is no state licensing system yet and the right to own marijuana is already legalized.
And there are still tricky technical issues that need to be addressed during this period, such as balancing the state&#39;s &quot;adequate access&quot; directive to licensed marijuana with a ban on the sale of it 1,000 feet from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens ...
“It will be especially difficult to locate licensed marijuana businesses within urban areas, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the newly formed Marijuana Legalization Center research group.
On November 21, Police Chief Oates of Aurora emailed his subordinates that the city&#39;s prosecutor&#39;s office would no longer prosecute individuals under the age of 21 for possession of small amounts of marijuana, and that the police will no longer convict people of these violations &quot;starting from now on&quot;.
Police Chief Oates said police will enforce the city&#39;s medical marijuana regulations and prosecute illegal drug dealers and distributors.
The North Colorado Weld County Attorney, Ken Buck, takes a more rigorous approach to this issue.
After voting on the bill, he said prosecutors would continue to prosecute marijuana possession, mainly to induce people who use it to get treatment.
At the moment, 119 people have been charged with possession of two or less ounces of marijuana, although many of them are accused of other violations.
“It is our institution&#39;s duty to prosecute acts that are considered criminal at the time they are committed,” Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The reaction was mixed, even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected a proposal to legalize marijuana.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, no longer prosecute adults for possession of small amounts of drugs.
District Attorney Pete Houtzinger upheld the decision, but also decided not to drop charges in already pending marijuana possession cases.
“I believe it is our direct responsibility to enforce the law until it changes,” he says.
Although 55% of Colorado residents who voted supported the decision, incorporating recreational marijuana issues into government and legal systems will not be easy.
And the controversial reactions of residents in different parts of the state exposed the ambiguity of the attitude of local authorities to the state&#39;s experiment with marijuana.
&quot;There is a cultural barrier for district attorneys on this issue,&quot; explains Sean McAlister, a Denver lawyer representing marijuana offenders and a local spokesman for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
&quot;They&#39;ve persecuted people for this for so long that now they can&#39;t really come to terms with the fact that this is no longer a crime,&quot; he says.
Colorado and Washington - the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana in the same way as alcohol - are destined to become a nationwide experimental field to test the very idea of legalizing drugs.
Legalization advocates and state officials plan to expand the legalized trade, but at the same time they are anxiously awaiting guidance from the federal government, which still plans to view the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Proponents of legalizing marijuana are hoping the Justice Department will give in on this issue.
Despite several high-profile arrests of traffickers and patients who used marijuana for medical reasons, the federal government has largely approved the medical marijuana trade in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Drug Enforcement Bureau agents are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small packet of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former adviser on affairs. the fight against drugs in the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for federal action.
Even before the presidential election, some local administrations approved a moratorium on the opening of new marijuana stores that would not have been able to open earlier than a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, brought forward a six-month ban on the marijuana trade, which is likely to be approved next week.
“We don’t want to be in a position where we license someone and then it will cause serious problems at the federal level,” says Bob Nicholson, a city councilor.
Our city voted against this amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still many unresolved issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I was kicked out of Oxford for being a Conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
As far back as I can remember, I have always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the best educational institution in the world, a modern analogue of the ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization - free thought and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of history at Worcester College, Oxford University in the late 1980s, I packed my bags and left, which was the first real scandal of my life.
My father broke down and cried.
The friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn&#39;t like my classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I left because I had to drink from chipped cups.
In fact, it was not that funny.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was systematically harassed and intimidated.
Not at all because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I went to a private school.
I was persecuted for only one reason, and in this illustrious cradle of enlightenment it looked like real barbarism and blind fanaticism: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a famous adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I myself was a supporter of the Conservatives.
You ask, why remember this now?
According to the latest data, a new generation of students with a center-right view is facing the same harassment.
This institutionalized and ever-growing hatred of Conservative students at Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection for their rights as that given to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives at the student club at Corpus Christi College in Cambridge say they are &quot;often actively isolated, personally attacked and made to feel unwelcome&quot; because of their political views.
They want to add an additional representative to the college&#39;s equal rights committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was further exacerbated by the recently released BBC 2 documentary on student politics, Wonderland: Young, Smart and Right, in which conservatives were portrayed as eccentric and neo-Nazis.
The film featured Joe Cook, the former president of the University of Oxford Conservatives&#39; Association, who drives a Rolls Royce, wears a silver suit and a silver-topped cane.
At other universities, conservative students complain that they are being made &quot;scapegoats for higher tuition fees.&quot;
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the University of Nottingham Conservative Association, said in a Sunday newspaper interview that “there is an increasing bias towards the left in the university environment.
People who don&#39;t even know us consider us in advance to be arrogant and violent children of rich parents with impunity. &quot;
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student at Corpus Christi College where the increased protection was requested, calls the atmosphere &quot;uncomfortable,&quot; and Stephanie Cherill, 19, the new president of the Conservative Association of Oxford University, says student club members&#39; attitudes towards bearers of center-right views has deteriorated significantly.
&quot;This poses a threat to both the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and simply to the normal life of club members,&quot; she says.
The first few weeks at Oxford, I was not just in the minority, I was alone.
I entered there in September 1986 as a timid and shy eighteen-year-old girl.
Oxford was feverish with hatred of the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university had voted out former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree due to budget cuts for higher education.
Even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable in such an atmosphere.
In the first days of the freshman week, when students get to know each other and with the teachers, I felt for the first time what lay ahead.
I did not know yet that the teachers not only turned a blind eye to the persecution of conservative students, but they themselves took part in it with pleasure.
Political issues - miners&#39; strike, privatization and government opposition to sanctions against the apartheid government in South Africa - permeated through the wood-paneled walls of the auditoriums.
In my first workshop, I needed to translate an eighteenth century French text into English, and I was not ready for what followed.
&quot;Miss Wyatt,&quot; said the late professor Harry Pitt, &quot;please translate the first paragraph.&quot;
The text was given to me with difficulty, I stumbled.
Harry Pitt was a very bitter man with a cake-like face.
&quot;Are the Thatcherites fundamentally not learning French or are they just lacking in brains?&quot; - he asked.
The other students giggled.
Tears came to my eyes.
&quot;I advise you to take some basic French lessons in your spare time, unless you are very busy moving around in society,&quot; Pitt muttered.
I returned to my room completely unhappy.
That evening in college, I sat alone at lunch; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a sophomore in English, who introduced himself as a member of the University&#39;s Association of Conservatives.
“I know who you are,” he said amiably.
- Unfortunately, this is the case:
anyone suspected of sympathizing with the Conservatives will be bullied.
It’s not easy for me myself, but in your case they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, therefore it will be more difficult for you.
Most Conservative freshmen pretend to be Labor. &quot;
Later, at a local pub, I cowardly tried to be a hypocrite.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything that Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick failed.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics, who himself studied at Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You&#39;re contagious. &quot;
Other students took up his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
“How do conservatives have sex?” Asked one of them.
&quot;They beat each other, don&#39;t they?&quot;
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the cancellation of the prosecution in the sixties.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or will I have to meet like-minded people only under cover of the night?
Will I be forced to become Labor and hide my true beliefs?
The three years ahead of me began to seem like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only teacher in my college who did not hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for being a Conservative, but also for being Thatcher&#39;s foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He barely showed up in college.
He despised him for his provinciality, pettiness and adherence to a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You won&#39;t be happy here,” he told me.
I began to travel to Oxford from my parental home in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased friends from the capital.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and explained the reason.
He didn&#39;t believe me.
During his studies in the forties, any political views were accepted there.
“But this is the best university in the world,” he said plaintively.
“They’re not capable of that, just not in the city of slumbering spiers ...
Even my communist friends have always behaved impeccably. &quot;
His wet eyes were dim.
&quot;Don&#39;t make hasty decisions.
I&#39;m sure this is just a joke.
You will break my heart if you leave university. &quot;
I was exhausted from the constant travel to London and my emotional defenses were weakening.
My friend, also a conservative, could not bear the pressure and gave up his beliefs.
The next week, during a seminar, when another history teacher quite seriously called me an &quot;enemy of the people&quot;, I decided to do the same.
Burning with shame in my soul, I confessed that “my parents had brainwashed me” and called them “old fools”.
The respite was short-lived.
The final nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was destined to be hammered by my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns every week for Rupert Murdoch&#39;s publications.
My door was locked.
I did not go out, and after five minutes my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a crybaby and a rag.
But at eighteen, no one should be the target of such anger and intimidation in school.
It is all the sadder that it was Oxford, which not only graduated fourteen Tory prime ministers, but to this day hides behind the undeserved reputation of a university that values equality and free thought.
&quot;Valentino prefers elegance to glory&quot;
ABC talks to Nati Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemica and other famous clients of the Italian designer about Valentino: Master of Sewing, which opened this week in London.
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of Valentino: Master of Sewing, a triumphant retrospective that brings together over 130 haute couture dresses his house has created over the past 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says with his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is &quot;Il Signoret&quot; Garavani, but it could not have been written without his eminent clients.
Valentino always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of the nobility.
The first hall of this exhibition, open until March 3, is replete with personal letters and photographs signed by the most distinguished aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie-Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino displays these personal memories as trophies of his social upsurge: from the humble tailor from the city of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international &quot;elite&quot;.
There is nothing wrong with being in love with the royal court.
“At least they don’t extinguish their cigarette butts on your gorgeous carpet like some great pop stars do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemica.
In the 60s and 70s we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an unparalleled host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
“We all enjoyed coming to his chalet in Gstaad,” explains Heini&#39;s ex-wife Thyssen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenia Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to glory.
And despite this, he is a star.
Valeria Mazza representing Valentino
Argentinean model Valeria Mazza recalls the charismatic fashion designer.
One day we went to dinner at his house, after the fashion show in the Plaza de España in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty invited were Sharon Stone and John F. Kennedy Jr.
Valentino&#39;s style manifested itself in everything - in every detail of his apartment, in its decoration, in food, in music.
&quot;Valentino made each of the guests feel important and loved,&quot; recalls the &quot;top model&quot;, whose work with the couturier began in 1995 during the Haute Couture Week in Paris.
“He never goes out of style because his sketches are real works of art,” she finishes.
The pedigree parade
The life of Garavani is not a story of obsessions, but of falling in love with complete reciprocity.
He loves people with good upbringing and high titles, and they love him.
One of the Somerset House galleries has been transformed into a glamorous 60-meter-long catwalk that offers a role reversal: the visitor takes the place of the models and must parade the catwalk, contemplating the &quot;spectators&quot; from dreams, sparkling with masterpieces from Valentino, such as the dress she chose Jacqueline Kennedy for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, the costume worn by Monica Vitti in Night, or the wool and leather coat that belonged to Empress Farah Diba.
In this audience of models such names as Sibylla of Luxembourg, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit from Norway, Rosario from Bulgaria or Sofia Habsburg shine.
Nati Abascal and fashion designer, in 2006
Many of these clients say that the first Valentino is like the first love, &quot;it is impossible to forget.&quot;
