Hardest profession in the world: miners from Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by hauling 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano along steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, while others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living mining sulfur in the Kawah Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the very bottom of the crater, where the sulfurous gas rising from the depths of the Earth solidifies upon contact with air.
He splits off huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, loads the baskets on his shoulders and carries them up the steep rocky road.
The peak of the volcano, which is 2,386 meters high, is only 250 meters, but emaciated loaders take more than 40 minutes to climb at a snail&#39;s pace, with difficulty maintaining balance and carefully feeling the way so as not to stumble or fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to a tourist from France who fell several years ago from the rocks of Kawah Ijen.
Miners from Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulfur they mine
Once at the top, they make their way between tourists, who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, wearily carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales, which the mining company placed just above, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
We are talking about PT Kandy Ngrimbi, the company that has been operating this volcano since 1960 and, better not to say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupiah (5 euro cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry, as the mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
&quot;Since carrying 70 kilograms is the norm, we earn about Rs 46,000 (3.8 euros) for each trip,&quot; explains Anto, who usually does three daily transports.
He spends three hours on each and feels overwhelmed in the end, but they allow him to save 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
While this seems like a minuscule for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the field.
&quot;The daily wages for miners are very high by local standards, where they pay 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day to collect coffee and an average monthly wage of 2 million rupees (167 euros),&quot; explains a loader who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali. ...
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the plot was not that hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason, which in Indonesia is as devastating as sulfur: &quot;I married a girl from Bali, where there are only Hindus, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam.&quot;
Anto has asthma, has difficulty breathing, constantly coughs and watery eyes due to toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kawah-Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, has difficulty breathing, constantly coughs, and has watery eyes from the toxic gases that the volcano gives off.
This is the price he must pay to achieve his dream.
&quot;I&#39;ll work for another two years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French,&quot; he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this pleasant and intelligent young man might be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist at a hotel, but instead he is doing the work of a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning, because the sulfur never stops flowing out at night, when its characteristic yellow turns to blue and glistens in the darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, illuminating his path with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
About 400 porters drag baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high margins, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs, and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own account and with such hardships.
In fact, they don&#39;t even get a fraction of the Rs 30,000 (€ 2.5) photography fee, which, along with the Rs 15,000 (€ 1.2) admission ticket, the guards of this reserve charge tourists who come to take pictures of the volcano and his mule people.
&quot;This job is for livestock, not people,&quot; says Badrusin, a stocky 42-year-old porter who has spent three decades on Kawah Ijen since he left college.
Able to lift up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will tolerate work &quot;as much as he can&quot; because he needs money to educate his three children aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here, because the volcano is my whole life
Although sulfur burns their throats and burns their eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches the miners in dense columns of smoke emerging from the volcano, they are so hardy that no one complains about their serious illnesses ... more serious, obviously, than their usual problems with breathing, arthrosis, knee pain and ulcers on the shoulders, which are deformed under the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can now only lift 50 kilograms in his 53 years.
Every day, he and his comrades carry 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks to a warehouse in Tamansari, overcoming a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path among thickets.
&quot;I will not retire, I will die here, because the volcano is my whole life,&quot; Unainik declares, opening his mouth wide, missing a few teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates, from generation to generation, one of the hardest occupations in the world: what the human mules of Kawah Ijen do.
