However, he acknowledges that the new regulations provide clearer guidance for developers who have previously been barred from offering too many small apartments in a project.
Too overstressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, after talking to Singaporeans who work in the center&#39;s financial district, it seems like they won&#39;t have much of an effect.
“People are very overworked, housing is expensive, as well as education, and because of this, many people are putting it off,” says the young executive.
Other people may have children.
“But it’s important for me to have my own money and time,” says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and housing and education prices as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how hard the government tries to encourage its citizens to have children, when it comes to childbirth, the Singaporeans have the final say.
