So, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute for Social Protection did not want to say goodbye to him, &quot;because he had a cut.&quot;
In other words, in those days it was a death sentence to have AIDS.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do it without compromising the quality of life.
However, unaware of their illness, many people still come when the virus has already caused damage, &quot;depleted&quot; their immune system and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, &quot;a great achievement at the moment is that the survival of the patient who starts treatment on time, and the survival of the general population are exactly the same,&quot; said the head of the HIV department HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, citing the fact that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectionist and HIV / AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have come to the conclusion that AIDS is not a death sentence, but life expectancy and quality of life depend on the degree of damage to the immune system that patients have at the beginning of diagnosis, with a better expected duration lives of those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years with a 200 CD4 count, and up to 50 years when a 500 CD4 count is reported.
In simple terms, the above means that someone who is diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25, according to these terms, &quot;by maintaining control, will be able to live without problems until the age of 75,&quot; he explained.
To appreciate this progress, it should be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS fell from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of patients died in the national database.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there have already been 187 deaths by May of this year; however, it is argued that there has been widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
- Personally, it seems to me that the problem is not in access to treatment.
This is how I imagine it, this is how things are in our hospital.
For at least the last 12 years we have not had a shortage of medicines, the problem is that patients come very late, because they do not know about their infected condition, that is, in the late stages of the disease.
He cited devastating data: &quot;Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some kind of opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose at an earlier stage, and therefore it is necessary to provide samples for detection in on a massive scale, for all people who ask for it. &quot;
Specialists and officials from the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (COESIDA) agree in their proposal, as well as patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who turned to a private laboratory for testing, prompted only by the fact that his friend did it and, despite his young age, he was already at the stage of AIDS and even suffered from Kaposi&#39;s sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they will die and do not want to know anything.
&quot;If I die anyway, I&#39;d rather get drunk three times a week,&quot; they say. But not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, exercise, take medication.
Today, his parents only know that he has suffered cancer.
I live a normal life like anyone else.
&quot;I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and the other person,&quot; listed Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO in order to encourage those who are in fear now in the context of World AIDS Day.
Let them be checked, if there was a risk of infection, let them find out as soon as possible if they are HIV-positive, it’s better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them find out that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
This post summarizes the fight against AIDS this 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are gaps between health programs and the common citizen, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara-based journalist who has tackled the HIV problem.
And the biggest is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, “in fact, the distribution of condoms has increased, before we were given one or two, now we are given packages of a hundred, which is very good, but it turns out that there are those who still do not have access to condom, &quot;he said.
Adolescents are among the most vulnerable to new infections.
&quot;Why do you need them?&quot; it is a popular question, with malice and condemnation, from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy staff and health workers, that teenagers do not want to hear, the propagandist assured.
I propose to change this inefficient allocation; so that condoms are not only behind the shelves and that hundreds of them are in vending machines in public toilets in places frequented by young people.
This is not an encouragement of promiscuity.
It&#39;s not about paying for a beer and a motel, Governor Emilio Gonzalez replied when asked if condom distribution was possible under his leadership.
&quot;This is not sexuality, it is best to make condoms available to those who are already sexually active,&quot; he said.
Key data in Jalisco
13,435 total cases were registered (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks 4th in the national rankings for new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th for HIV.
92% of infections are in the genital tract, 6% through the blood and 2% in the perinatal tract.
It is estimated that 50 thousand people can live with HIV, since there are 4 to 5 people per registered case who do not know about it.
Given the ratification by the United States Court of Appeal of the decision that reverses the Vitro Group&#39;s debt restructuring achieved through bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico, the scenario sets a fateful precedent for any national company with subsidiaries in a neighboring country that has solvency problems.
It seems that the procedures to support the survival of firms, which are permitted by Mexican law, are not valid in the land of stripes and stars, contrary to international agreements.
In practical terms, the June 15 approval of Judge Harleen Hale&#39;s decision in the Texas North District bankruptcy court leaves Mexican firms defenseless in the face of seizure of property on the other side of the Rio Grande.
However, the ruling opens the door for Mexico&#39;s leading glass manufacturer to the United States Supreme Court, citing three inconsistencies.
As an introduction, while the judge of the case notes that creditors should be governed by the US Bankruptcy Code, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, located in New Orleans, says that the main proceedings relate to the bankruptcy proceedings pending in Mexico.
The first point implies the cancellation of international judicial cooperation in cases of insolvency of enterprises of a transnational profile.
In fact, for this purpose, the UN Model Law on the Unification of International Trade Law was created, defining the American Institute of Law as the arbiter.
Secondly, the verdict establishes that without an inter-firm vote, the debts that Vitro subsidiaries owed to the parent company to the parent company, recognized in the critical mass of bankruptcy proceedings, would not have reached the majority required to approve the restructuring.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, Vitro was not the first time this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intercompany debt was guaranteed by the Federal Institution of Bankruptcy Proceedings.
It is also true that by subtracting the affiliates&#39; votes, Vitro&#39;s creditors who fought against it in the United States courts, vulture funds like Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have reached the majority.
The vote would be 45 percent to 37 percent.
The Court of Appeal omits these data.
On the other hand, he blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008, affected by the severe economic crisis that hit the United States, striking the country.
So far, the firm of the Gonzalez Sada family will appeal the decision to the Court of Appeal itself, so that the vote reaches its plenum, that is, five judges, since only three voted.
Failure to do so will result in a petition for certification that will require a review of the process by a higher court, in this case the United States Supreme Court.
Worst of all, the court rejected a document sent by the Mexican government in the role of amicus curiae (&quot;friend of the court&quot;), which describes the process that Vitro follows under the Bankruptcy Proceedings Act, signaling that it is exempting itself from complying with agreements. signed by both countries to link it to Section 15 of the US Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, it is noted that the country has submitted to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, that is, the rules established for cases of interstate insolvency, which guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
