I remember winning the first time against the United States during the 1989 Olympic qualifier in Mexico.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, in which we got fourth place and it should have been bronze, if not for the Canadian referee who forced us to replay the final game, Reyes said.
That team from the 1990 World Cup is the best team you&#39;ve ever seen?
She is among the best, just like the one that won the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the one from the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and beat the US team, which was quite similar to the one that won us bronze in the World Cup.
That team not only played again Minsi, Gauss, Ramon Rivas, Fico Lopez and &#39;Pikulin&#39; (Ortiz), but also young (Javier) &#39;Tonito&#39; Colon and James Carter, brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario &#39;Quixote&#39; Morales, who was unable to compete in 90 due to a knee injury.
The team that may not have been the best in terms of personnel, but brought us a gold medal and a lot of joy, was the team for the 1995 Olympic qualifying tournament in Neuquen, Argentina.
With role-playing players like &#39;Canito&#39; Nieves, Pablo Alisea and young Rolando Hurruitner replacing players suspended for the mess in the Pan American Championship in Mar del Plata, we won gold against all expectations.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it was Pikulin Ortiz.
His performance in international tournaments is impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level the way Pikulin did.
And that&#39;s without considering his career in the various leagues he played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
That&#39;s a very difficult question.
We had very good youngsters including Julio Toro, Flora Melendez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
As a young person, I really like the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider to be your main achievement in the federation?
Participated in the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and that in the early 90s BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What is left for you to do?
There were things that I wanted to implement, like regionalization of smaller categories.
For example, for the boys from Ponce to play only in their own area and only against teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Now the guys travel and play too much, and this is unnecessary.
At least I see the fruits of the mandatory certification and course for managers, officials and judges.
It gives me pleasure.
What are you doing now?
Most of all I listen to music, watch music videos of my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren, and occasionally go to basketball games.
And, of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Died actor Larry Hagman
Born September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, Larry Hagman became world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as &quot;J.R.&quot; , angry and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil predator JR Ewing on the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned as JR this year for Dallas&#39;s new season, died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., Dallas&#39;s production studio.
“Larry is back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the iconic role he loved the most,” his family said.
Larry&#39;s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas at the Thanksgiving Fair.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and in the sequel, was next to Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, her spokesman Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to everyone who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented and I will miss him very much.
&quot;He was an original person and lived a full life,&quot; Gray confirmed in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and admitted to drinking for years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and underwent a transplant.
Long before Dallas, Hagman rose to prominence on television for his role as the decent guy in the light comedy &quot;I Dream of Jeannie,&quot; which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive genie girl, played by Barbara Eden, and begins living with her under the same roof.
He also starred in two rarely-aired comedies, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His film work has included critically acclaimed roles in The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was his masterful interpretation of the deliciously hideous JR that brought Hagman to the top of his stardom.
A CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its environment aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan &quot;Who Shot JR?&quot;, Conceived to create a buzz around the emotional episode in which Hagman&#39;s character is nearly killed, has spawned international debate and millions of dollars being risked at the bookmakers.
It also helped to attract a record audience to the series at that time.
When answered in the November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers watched it and made Dallas the second most viewed entertainment program in history, after the 1983 MASH finale, which attracted 50 million viewers.
It was JR&#39;s sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
JR interfered with her and then threatened her that he would accuse her of prostitution if she didn&#39;t get out of town, but others had reasons to attack him as well.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupt official with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be placed on treatment.
&quot;I know what should be on JR&#39;s tombstone,&quot; Hagman said in 1988.
It should be said, &quot;Here lies the honest citizen JR Ewing.&quot;
This is the only trade he lost.
Victoria Principal, also the heroine of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone &quot;huge, both on and off the screen.&quot;
He is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of admirers around the world, and in the hearts of each of us who are fortunate enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new Dallas episode aired a few months ago to great acclaim on TNT.
The recording of five episodes of the second season had already been completed and the sixth was in production, the channel said.
Warner or TNT have yet to make any statements about what will happen to the series after Hagman leaves.
