Each week, students explore apocalyptic phenomena such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
This semester, when professor of religion Stuart Sharme decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible bait: the end of the Mayan calendar&#39;s &quot;long countdown&quot;, December 21, which many people have seized upon as proof that the end of the world is coming. ...
But Sharme had no idea what awaited him in the next couple of months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the financial crisis that some call &quot;long-armageddon,&quot; and the growing conflict that would involve Israel, a place where end-time Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
&quot;I didn&#39;t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester of them all,&quot; Sharma told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
